// Unit 31: Wirtschaft
// Level: B2

const UNIT_31 =
{n:31,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Wirtschaft",sub:"Angebot und Nachfrage",icon:"💼",level:"B2.2",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
{id:"deu_r31l1",title:"Der Steuerberater",icon:"\uD83D\uDCCA",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Der Steuerberater",desc:"Enter the world of German taxes and finance. Learn the key financial words. Understand how the German tax system shapes daily life.",goals:["Learn 18 core words from tax and finance","Understand Umsatz, Gewinn, Verlust, and Kredit","Experience Verumius's first tax consultation"]},

{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"tense",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-office",trg:"Das Buero des Steuerberaters ist makellos. Gerahmte Zertifikate an der Wand. Ein Desktop zeigt Steuersoftware mit Zahlenkolonnen. Verumius sitzt gegenueber, sein Ordner mit zerknitterten Belegen wirkt peinlich neben dem farbcodierten Ablagesystem des Beraters.",src:"The tax advisor's office is immaculate. Framed certificates line the wall. A desktop shows tax software with columns of numbers. Verumius sits across, his folder of crumpled receipts looking embarrassingly casual next to the advisor's color-coded filing system."},

{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"calm",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-desk",trg:"Guten Tag, Herr Verumius. Lassen Sie uns Ihre Steuersituation besprechen. Da Sie freiberuflich arbeiten, muessen wir einige Punkte klaeren.",src:"Good day, Mr Verumius. Let us discuss your tax situation. Since you work freelance, we need to clarify a few points."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",art:"de-ber-verumius-receipts",trg:"Ich habe alle Belege mitgebracht. Ich hoffe, das reicht?",src:"I brought all the receipts. I hope that is enough?"},

{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"professional",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-screen",trg:"Das sehen wir uns an. Bis Ende des Monats werden Sie Ihre Steuererklaerung abgegeben haben. Keine Sorge.",src:"We will take a look. By the end of the month you will have submitted your tax return. No worries."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Abgabe",src:"levy, tax, submission",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Ab (off/away) + Gabe (giving). Both the act of handing in\nand the money you hand to the state.",example:"A: Welche Abgaben muss ich zahlen?\nB: Sozialabgaben und Steuern.\nA: Wie hoch sind die Abgaben insgesamt?\nB: Etwa 40 Prozent vom Bruttolohn.",exampleSrc:"A: Which levies do I have to pay?\nB: Social contributions and taxes.\nA: How high are the levies in total?\nB: About 40 percent of gross wages.",funFact:"'Ab' (off/away) + 'Gabe' (giving). A levy, a tax, or a submission. Die Abgabe covers both the act of handing something in and the money you hand over to the state. 'Sozialabgaben' (social contributions) eat roughly 40% of German gross income."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Umsatz",src:"revenue, turnover",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Um (around) + Satz (rate/set). What comes in before costs.\n'Umsatzsteuer' (VAT) is 19% on almost everything.",example:"A: Wie hoch war Ihr Umsatz letztes Jahr?\nB: Ungefaehr 80.000 Euro.\nA: Und nach Abzug der Kosten?\nB: Dann bleibt der Gewinn uebrig.",exampleSrc:"A: How high was your revenue last year?\nB: About 80,000 euros.\nA: And after deducting costs?\nB: Then the profit remains.",funFact:"'Um' (around) + 'Satz' (rate/set). Revenue, turnover. Der Umsatz is what comes in before costs. 'Umsatzsteuer' (sales tax/VAT) is Germany's 19% on almost everything. The word literally means 'conversion rate' of goods to money."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Gewinn",src:"profit",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'gewinnen' (to win/gain). What remains after all costs.\n'Gewinn und Verlust' is the fundamental equation.",example:"A: Hat die Firma Gewinn gemacht?\nB: Ja, der Gewinn war hoeher als erwartet.\nA: Wie berechnet man den Gewinn?\nB: Umsatz minus Kosten gleich Gewinn.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company make a profit?\nB: Yes, the profit was higher than expected.\nA: How do you calculate profit?\nB: Revenue minus costs equals profit.",funFact:"From 'gewinnen' (to win/gain). Profit. Der Gewinn is what remains after all costs. 'Gewinn und Verlust' (profit and loss) is the fundamental equation of every business. Winning in business is literally called Gewinn."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Verlust",src:"loss",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From 'verlieren' (to lose). The opposite of Gewinn.\n'Verluste machen' is every entrepreneur's nightmare.",example:"A: Hat das Unternehmen Verlust gemacht?\nB: Leider ja. Der Verlust war erheblich.\nA: Kann man Verluste steuerlich absetzen?\nB: Ja, Verluste mindern die Steuerlast.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company make a loss?\nB: Unfortunately yes. The loss was considerable.\nA: Can you deduct losses from taxes?\nB: Yes, losses reduce the tax burden.",funFact:"From 'verlieren' (to lose). Loss. Der Verlust. The opposite of Gewinn. 'Verluste machen' (to make losses) is every entrepreneur's nightmare. The -ust ending comes from the old past participle of verlieren."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Schulden",src:"debts",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"From 'Schuld' (guilt/debt). Always plural for money owed.\nIn German, debt and guilt share the same root.",example:"A: Hat er Schulden?\nB: Ja, hohe Schulden bei der Bank.\nA: Kann man Schulden abbauen?\nB: Mit einem guten Plan schon.",exampleSrc:"A: Does he have debts?\nB: Yes, high debts at the bank.\nA: Can you reduce debts?\nB: With a good plan, yes.",funFact:"From 'Schuld' (guilt/debt). Debts. Die Schulden is always plural when meaning money owed. In German, debt and guilt share the same root. 'Schulden haben' (to have debts) carries a moral weight the English word does not."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Kredit",src:"loan, credit",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'creditum' (something entrusted). 'Einen Kredit\naufnehmen' (to take out a loan).",example:"A: Brauchen Sie einen Kredit?\nB: Ja, fuer mein neues Buero.\nA: Bei welcher Bank nehmen Sie den Kredit auf?\nB: Bei der Sparkasse. Die Konditionen sind gut.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you need a loan?\nB: Yes, for my new office.\nA: At which bank will you take out the loan?\nB: At the Sparkasse. The conditions are good.",funFact:"From Latin 'creditum' (something entrusted). A loan, a credit. 'Einen Kredit aufnehmen' (to take out a loan). The Schufa (credit score agency) tracks every German's credit history. Without a good Schufa score, renting an apartment is nearly impossible."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Zinssatz",src:"interest rate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Zins (interest) + Satz (rate). 'Zins' comes from Latin 'census.'\nThe ECB in Frankfurt sets the base rate for all of Europe.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist der Zinssatz?\nB: Aktuell bei 3,5 Prozent.\nA: Ist der Zinssatz gestiegen?\nB: Ja, die Europaeische Zentralbank hat ihn erhoeht.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is the interest rate?\nB: Currently at 3.5 percent.\nA: Has the interest rate risen?\nB: Yes, the European Central Bank raised it.",funFact:"'Zins' (interest) + 'Satz' (rate). Interest rate. 'Zins' comes from Latin 'census.' The European Central Bank in Frankfurt sets the base Zinssatz for all of Europe. Germany's Sparer (savers) watch this number obsessively."},

{type:"teach",trg:"das Kapital",src:"capital",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'capitalis' (of the head). Both money invested\nand the title of Marx's famous book.",example:"A: Haben Sie genuegend Kapital?\nB: Nein, ich brauche mehr Kapital fuer die Expansion.\nA: Eigenkapital oder Fremdkapital?\nB: Am liebsten Eigenkapital.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have sufficient capital?\nB: No, I need more capital for the expansion.\nA: Equity or borrowed capital?\nB: Preferably equity.",funFact:"From Latin 'capitalis' (of the head). Capital. Karl Marx wrote 'Das Kapital' in London about Berlin's industrialists. The word means both money invested and the book that changed economic theory forever."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Haushalt",src:"household, budget",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Haus (house) + halt (keeping). Both family budget and\nfederal budget use the same word.",example:"A: Wie sieht Ihr Haushalt aus?\nB: Mein Familienhaushalt ist stabil.\nA: Und der Bundeshaushalt?\nB: Der ist komplizierter. Milliarden Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: How does your budget look?\nB: My family budget is stable.\nA: And the federal budget?\nB: That is more complicated. Billions of euros.",funFact:"'Haus' (house) + 'halt' (keeping). A household or a budget. 'Bundeshaushalt' (federal budget) and 'Familienhaushalt' (family budget) use the same word. Running a country is like running a household, linguistically."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Etat",src:"budget (public)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From French 'etat' (state/budget). Borrowed during\nPrussian administration. More elegant than Haushalt.",example:"A: Der Etat fuer Bildung ist gestiegen.\nB: Das ist gut. Bildung braucht Geld.\nA: Wer entscheidet ueber den Etat?\nB: Das Parlament. Jedes Jahr neu.",exampleSrc:"A: The budget for education has risen.\nB: That is good. Education needs money.\nA: Who decides about the budget?\nB: Parliament. Every year anew.",funFact:"From French 'etat' (state/budget). A budget, especially a public one. Borrowed from French during Prussian administration. 'Etat' sounds more elegant than 'Haushalt' in political contexts. German newspapers love the French flair."},

{type:"teach",trg:"finanziell",src:"financial",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From French 'financiel,' from Latin 'finis' (end/settlement).\nStress on the last syllable: fi-nan-tsi-ELL.",example:"A: Wie ist Ihre finanzielle Situation?\nB: Finanziell bin ich stabil.\nA: Finanziell unabhaengig zu sein ist das Ziel.\nB: Ja, das ist der Traum vieler Deutscher.",exampleSrc:"A: How is your financial situation?\nB: Financially I am stable.\nA: Being financially independent is the goal.\nB: Yes, that is the dream of many Germans.",funFact:"From French 'financiel,' from Latin 'finis' (end/settlement). Financial. 'Finanziell unabhaengig' (financially independent) is the German dream alongside 'Eigenheim' (own home). Stress on the last syllable: fi-nan-tsi-ELL."},

{type:"teach",trg:"oekonomisch",src:"economic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Greek 'oikonomikos' (household management).\nOikos (house) + nomos (law). Laws of the household.",example:"A: Die oekonomische Lage hat sich verbessert.\nB: Ja, die oekonomischen Daten sind positiv.\nA: Was bedeutet oekonomisch genau?\nB: Alles, was mit Wirtschaft zu tun hat.",exampleSrc:"A: The economic situation has improved.\nB: Yes, the economic data is positive.\nA: What does economic mean exactly?\nB: Everything related to the economy.",funFact:"From Greek 'oikonomikos' (household management). The Greek roots are oikos (house) + nomos (law). Economics literally means 'laws of the household.' The German spelling with oe- preserves the Greek origin."},

{type:"teach",trg:"nachhaltig",src:"sustainable, lasting",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Nach (after) + haltig (holding). Originally a forestry term:\nonly cut as many trees as can regrow.",example:"A: Ist diese Investition nachhaltig?\nB: Ja, sie bringt langfristigen Gewinn.\nA: Nachhaltigkeit ist auch gut fuer die Umwelt.\nB: Und fuer die Wirtschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: Is this investment sustainable?\nB: Yes, it brings long-term profit.\nA: Sustainability is also good for the environment.\nB: And for the economy.",funFact:"'Nach' (after) + 'haltig' (holding). Originally a forestry term: only cut as many trees as can regrow. Germany coined Nachhaltigkeit in 1713. Now it appears everywhere: 'nachhaltige Wirtschaft' (sustainable economy)."},

{type:"teach",trg:"rentabel",src:"profitable, yielding returns",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From 'Rente' (return/pension) + '-abel' (able).\nIf something is rentabel, it gives back more than you put in.",example:"A: Ist das Projekt rentabel?\nB: Ja, die Rendite liegt bei 8 Prozent.\nA: Ab wann wird es rentabel?\nB: Voraussichtlich nach zwei Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the project profitable?\nB: Yes, the return is at 8 percent.\nA: From when will it be profitable?\nB: Presumably after two years.",funFact:"From 'Rente' (return/pension) + '-abel' (able). Profitable, yielding returns. 'Eine rentable Investition' (a profitable investment). Related to Rendite (yield). If something is rentabel, it gives back more than you put in."},

{type:"teach",trg:"wirtschaften",src:"to manage finances, to economize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From 'Wirt' (host/innkeeper). 'Gut wirtschaften' means\nto manage money well. The innkeeper as original economist.",example:"A: Wie wirtschaftest du mit deinem Geld?\nB: Ich spare jeden Monat etwas.\nA: Gut wirtschaften ist eine Kunst.\nB: Vor allem, wenn die Preise steigen.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you manage your money?\nB: I save something every month.\nA: Managing money well is an art.\nB: Especially when prices rise.",funFact:"From 'Wirt' (host/innkeeper). To manage finances, to economize. 'Gut wirtschaften' (to manage money well). The innkeeper who runs a good house is the original economist. 'Hauswirtschaft' (home economics) uses the same root."},

{type:"teach",trg:"finanzieren",src:"to finance",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From French 'financer.' Non-separable -ieren verb.\nAlways stresses the -ier- syllable.",example:"A: Wie finanzieren Sie das Projekt?\nB: Durch einen Kredit.\nA: Kann man es auch anders finanzieren?\nB: Ja, durch Investoren oder Eigenkapital.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you finance the project?\nB: Through a loan.\nA: Can you also finance it differently?\nB: Yes, through investors or equity.",funFact:"From French 'financer.' To finance. 'Ein Projekt finanzieren' (to finance a project). The -ieren ending marks it as a French/Latin loan verb. These verbs never separate and always stress the -ier- syllable."},

{type:"teach",trg:"investieren",src:"to invest",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'investire' (to clothe). You 'clothe' your money\nin an asset. Non-separable -ieren verb.",example:"A: Worin investieren Sie?\nB: In Immobilien und Aktien.\nA: Lohnt es sich, in Deutschland zu investieren?\nB: Ja, der Markt ist stabil.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you invest in?\nB: In real estate and stocks.\nA: Is it worth investing in Germany?\nB: Yes, the market is stable.",funFact:"From Latin 'investire' (to clothe). To invest. You 'clothe' your money in an asset. 'In Aktien investieren' (to invest in stocks). The metaphor: money gets dressed up and goes to work."},

{type:"teach",trg:"jaehrlich",src:"annually, yearly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Jahr (year) + -lich. The umlaut pattern:\nTag/taeglich, Monat/monatlich, Jahr/jaehrlich.",example:"A: Wie oft muessen Sie die Steuererklaerung machen?\nB: Jaehrlich. Einmal pro Jahr.\nA: Und die jaehrlichen Kosten?\nB: Die berechnet der Steuerberater.",exampleSrc:"A: How often do you have to do the tax return?\nB: Annually. Once per year.\nA: And the annual costs?\nB: The tax advisor calculates those.",funFact:"'Jahr' (year) + '-lich' (adjective suffix). Annually, yearly. 'Jaehrliche Steuererklaerung' (annual tax return). The umlaut pattern: Tag/taeglich, Monat/monatlich, Jahr/jaehrlich."},

{type:"mc",q:"Der Steuerberater prueft Verumius' Finanzen. Die Gesamteinnahmen vor Abzug aller Kosten heissen...",opts:["Gewinn","Umsatz","Kapital","Verlust"],ans:"Umsatz",hint:"What comes in before anything is deducted. The opposite of 'after costs.'"},

{type:"mc",q:"Verumius fragt nach seinem Zinssatz. Wonach fragt er?",opts:["nach dem Zinssatz (interest rate)","nach der Gewinnmarge","nach dem Steuersatz","nach dem Schuldenniveau"],ans:"nach dem Zinssatz (interest rate)",hint:"'Zins' comes from Latin 'census.' 'Satz' means rate. What the bank charges for borrowed money."},

{type:"fb",s:"Da er Schulden hat, muss Verumius einen {1} aufnehmen.",a:["Kredit"],opts:["Kredit","Gewinn","Umsatz","Etat"],hint:"When you owe money and need more, you take out a ...",sSrc:"Since he has debts, Verumius must take out a loan."},

{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-handshake",trg:"Machen Sie sich keine Sorgen, Herr Verumius. Bis Ende des Monats werden wir Ihre Steuererklaerung fertig haben. Dann sieht alles klarer aus.",src:"Do not worry, Mr. Verumius. By the end of the month we will have your tax return finished. Then everything will look clearer."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"relieved",art:"de-ber-verumius-leaving-office",trg:"Danke. Ich dachte, Steuern in Deutschland waeren unmoeglich. Aber mit einem guten Steuerberater ist es machbar.",src:"Thank you. I thought taxes in Germany would be impossible. But with a good tax advisor, it is doable."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l2",title:"Die Sprache des Geldes",icon:"\uD83D\uDCB0",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Sprache des Geldes",desc:"Learn the language of investments and the stock market. Understand how Germans talk about money and markets. Master the financial register.",goals:["Learn 20 words about investment and stock market","Understand Aktie, Anlage, Rendite, and Konjunktur","Build your financial vocabulary"]},

{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"observant",art:"de-ber-cafe-newspaper",trg:"Ein Cafe in Mitte. Verumius blättert durch das Handelsblatt. Aktie, Konjunktur, Rendite: jede Zeile eine neue Welt. Er nimmt einen Stift und faengt an, Woerter zu unterstreichen.",src:"A cafe in Mitte. Verumius leafs through the Handelsblatt. Aktie, Konjunktur, Rendite: every line a new world. He picks up a pen and starts underlining words."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Aktie",src:"stock, share",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Dutch 'actie' (share of a company). Only about 17%\nof Germans own Aktien. Germans prefer Sparbuch.",example:"A: Hast du Aktien?\nB: Ja, ein paar DAX-Aktien.\nA: Sind die Aktien gestiegen?\nB: Letzte Woche ja, diese Woche nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have stocks?\nB: Yes, a few DAX stocks.\nA: Have the stocks risen?\nB: Last week yes, this week no.",funFact:"From Dutch 'actie' (share of a company). A stock, a share. Germany's main stock index is the DAX (Deutscher Aktienindex). Only about 17% of Germans own Aktien, far less than Americans or British. Germans prefer Sparbuch (savings accounts)."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Anlage",src:"investment, system",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"An (at) + Lage (laying/position). Covers anything\nyou 'lay down' for future use.",example:"A: Welche Anlage empfehlen Sie?\nB: Eine sichere Geldanlage mit guter Rendite.\nA: Und eine Solaranlage?\nB: Das ist eine andere Art von Anlage.",exampleSrc:"A: Which investment do you recommend?\nB: A safe financial investment with good returns.\nA: And a solar system?\nB: That is a different type of Anlage.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'Lage' (laying/position). An investment, or a system/facility. 'Geldanlage' (financial investment), 'Solaranlage' (solar system). The word covers anything you 'lay down' for future use."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Anleger",src:"investor",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Anlage + -er (person). The person who lays down money.\n'Kleinanleger' vs. 'Grossanleger.'",example:"A: Sind Sie ein erfahrener Anleger?\nB: Nein, ich bin Kleinanleger.\nA: Was kaufen Kleinanleger meistens?\nB: ETFs und sichere Fonds.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you an experienced investor?\nB: No, I am a small investor.\nA: What do small investors usually buy?\nB: ETFs and safe funds.",funFact:"'Anlage' + '-er' (person). An investor. 'Kleinanleger' (small investors) vs. 'Grossanleger' (institutional investors). The person who lays down their money."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Boerse",src:"stock exchange",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From the Belgian family 'van der Beurze' who hosted\nmerchants in medieval Bruges.",example:"A: Was passiert heute an der Boerse?\nB: Die Kurse sind gefallen.\nA: Warum reagiert die Boerse so?\nB: Wegen der neuen Zinsentscheidung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is happening at the stock exchange today?\nB: Prices have fallen.\nA: Why does the stock exchange react like that?\nB: Because of the new interest rate decision.",funFact:"From the Belgian family 'van der Beurze' who hosted merchants in medieval Bruges. A stock exchange. The Frankfurt Boerse is Europe's third largest. The word traveled from a Belgian family name to every language."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Dividende",src:"dividend",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'dividendum' (that which is to be divided).\nGerman companies pay Dividenden once per year.",example:"A: Zahlt diese Aktie eine Dividende?\nB: Ja, einmal im Jahr.\nA: Wie hoch ist die Dividende?\nB: Drei Euro pro Aktie.",exampleSrc:"A: Does this stock pay a dividend?\nB: Yes, once a year.\nA: How high is the dividend?\nB: Three euros per share.",funFact:"From Latin 'dividendum' (that which is to be divided). A dividend. The share of profit divided among stockholders. German companies pay Dividenden once per year, unlike quarterly in the US."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Rendite",src:"return on investment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Italian 'rendita' (return/yield). Germans calculate\nRendite obsessively before investing.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist die Rendite?\nB: Ungefaehr fuenf Prozent pro Jahr.\nA: Ist das eine gute Rendite?\nB: Fuer eine sichere Anlage, ja.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is the return?\nB: About five percent per year.\nA: Is that a good return?\nB: For a safe investment, yes.",funFact:"From Italian 'rendita' (return/yield). Return on investment. Germans calculate Rendite obsessively before investing. The Italian banking term entered German via Venetian traders."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Investition",src:"investment (the act)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'investire.' Emphasizes the action of investing.\nAnlage emphasizes the asset you hold.",example:"A: Diese Investition ist riskant.\nB: Aber die Rendite koennte hoch sein.\nA: Jede Investition hat ein Risiko.\nB: Ohne Risiko keine Rendite.",exampleSrc:"A: This investment is risky.\nB: But the return could be high.\nA: Every investment has a risk.\nB: Without risk, no return.",funFact:"From Latin 'investire.' An investment (the act). Different nuance from Anlage: Investition emphasizes the action of investing, Anlage emphasizes the asset you hold."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Profit",src:"profit",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'profectus' (progress/gain). Less formal than Gewinn.\n'Profit machen' sounds slightly negative in German.",example:"A: Hat die Firma Profit gemacht?\nB: Ja, aber 'Gewinn erzielen' klingt besser.\nA: Warum klingt Profit negativ?\nB: Es klingt nach Gier. Gewinn ist neutral.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company make a profit?\nB: Yes, but 'to achieve profit' sounds better.\nA: Why does Profit sound negative?\nB: It sounds greedy. Gewinn is neutral.",funFact:"From Latin 'profectus' (progress/gain). Less formal than Gewinn. 'Profit machen' sounds slightly negative in German, implying greed. 'Gewinn erzielen' is the neutral business term."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Konzern",src:"corporation, conglomerate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'concernere' (to mix/relate). Larger than\nein Unternehmen: a group of companies under one roof.",example:"A: Siemens ist ein grosser Konzern.\nB: Ja, mit Tochterunternehmen weltweit.\nA: Was ist der Unterschied zum Unternehmen?\nB: Ein Konzern vereint mehrere Unternehmen.",exampleSrc:"A: Siemens is a large corporation.\nB: Yes, with subsidiaries worldwide.\nA: What is the difference from an enterprise?\nB: A corporation unites several enterprises.",funFact:"From Latin 'concernere' (to mix/relate). A corporation, a conglomerate. Siemens, Volkswagen, BASF are German Konzerne. A Konzern is larger than an Unternehmen: it is a group of companies under one roof."},

{type:"teach",trg:"das Unternehmen",src:"enterprise, company",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Unter (under) + nehmen (to take). Germany's Mittelstand\n(mid-sized Unternehmen) employ 60% of all workers.",example:"A: Was fuer ein Unternehmen ist das?\nB: Ein mittelstaendisches Unternehmen.\nA: Wie viele Mitarbeiter hat das Unternehmen?\nB: Etwa 200. Typischer Mittelstand.",exampleSrc:"A: What kind of company is that?\nB: A medium-sized enterprise.\nA: How many employees does the company have?\nB: About 200. Typical Mittelstand.",funFact:"'Unter' (under) + 'nehmen' (to take). An enterprise, a company. Germany's Mittelstand (mid-sized Unternehmen) employ 60% of all workers. The word means literally 'undertaking.'"},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Wettbewerb",src:"competition",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Wette (bet) + Bewerb (application/contest). Originally\na bet about who is better.",example:"A: Der Wettbewerb in dieser Branche ist hart.\nB: Ja, nur die Besten ueberleben.\nA: Ist freier Wettbewerb immer gut?\nB: Meistens. Er senkt die Preise.",exampleSrc:"A: The competition in this sector is tough.\nB: Yes, only the best survive.\nA: Is free competition always good?\nB: Mostly. It lowers prices.",funFact:"'Wette' (bet) + 'Bewerb' (application/contest). Competition. Originally a bet about who is better. 'Freier Wettbewerb' (free competition) is the foundation of Germany's soziale Marktwirtschaft."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Marktanteil",src:"market share",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Markt (market) + Anteil (share/portion). The metric\nevery Konzern watches most closely.",example:"A: Wie gross ist unser Marktanteil?\nB: Etwa 15 Prozent.\nA: Muessen wir den Marktanteil vergroessern?\nB: Ja, die Konkurrenz waechst.",exampleSrc:"A: How large is our market share?\nB: About 15 percent.\nA: Do we need to increase our market share?\nB: Yes, the competition is growing.",funFact:"'Markt' (market) + 'Anteil' (share/portion). Market share. 'Einen hohen Marktanteil haben' (to have a high market share). The metric every Konzern watches most closely."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Nachfrage",src:"demand",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Nach (after) + Frage (question/demand). Literally:\nasking after something you want.",example:"A: Die Nachfrage nach Elektroautos steigt.\nB: Ja, Angebot und Nachfrage bestimmen den Preis.\nA: Uebersteigt die Nachfrage das Angebot?\nB: Momentan ja.",exampleSrc:"A: The demand for electric cars is rising.\nB: Yes, supply and demand determine the price.\nA: Does demand exceed supply?\nB: Currently, yes.",funFact:"'Nach' (after) + 'Frage' (question/demand). Demand. 'Angebot und Nachfrage' (supply and demand) is Lesson 1 of every economics course. Literally: asking after something you want."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Konjunktur",src:"economic cycle, business climate",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'conjunctura' (joining together).\n'Konjunkturaufschwung' (boom), 'Konjunkturabschwung' (recession).",example:"A: Wie ist die Konjunktur gerade?\nB: Die Konjunktur erholt sich langsam.\nA: Kommt ein Konjunkturaufschwung?\nB: Die Experten sind optimistisch.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the economic climate right now?\nB: The economy is recovering slowly.\nA: Is an economic boom coming?\nB: The experts are optimistic.",funFact:"From Latin 'conjunctura' (joining together). The economic cycle, the business climate. 'Konjunkturaufschwung' (economic boom), 'Konjunkturabschwung' (recession). Germans track the Konjunktur like weather."},

{type:"teach",trg:"profitabel",src:"profitable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From French 'profitable.' Synonym of rentabel\nbut more international in tone. Both mean: it makes money.",example:"A: Ist das Geschaeft profitabel?\nB: Ja, seit dem zweiten Jahr.\nA: Was macht es profitabel?\nB: Niedrige Kosten und hohe Nachfrage.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the business profitable?\nB: Yes, since the second year.\nA: What makes it profitable?\nB: Low costs and high demand.",funFact:"From French 'profitable.' Profitable. 'Ein profitables Geschaeft' (a profitable business). Synonym of rentabel but more international in tone. Both mean: it makes money."},

{type:"teach",trg:"gewinnbringend",src:"profit-bringing, lucrative",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Gewinn (profit) + bringend (bringing). A compound\nparticiple adjective. German builds these freely.",example:"A: War die Strategie gewinnbringend?\nB: Ja, sehr gewinnbringend.\nA: Wie findet man gewinnbringende Projekte?\nB: Durch gute Marktanalyse.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the strategy lucrative?\nB: Yes, very lucrative.\nA: How do you find lucrative projects?\nB: Through good market analysis.",funFact:"'Gewinn' (profit) + 'bringend' (bringing). Profit-bringing, lucrative. 'Eine gewinnbringende Strategie' (a lucrative strategy). A compound participle adjective. German builds these freely: zeitsparend (time-saving), bahnbrechend (groundbreaking)."},

{type:"teach",trg:"wettbewerbsfaehig",src:"competitive, able to compete",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Wettbewerb (competition) + faehig (capable). At 19 letters,\na typical German compound. The Fugen-s is the glue.",example:"A: Sind unsere Preise wettbewerbsfaehig?\nB: Ja, wir sind guenstiger als die Konkurrenz.\nA: Wettbewerbsfaehig zu bleiben ist schwer.\nB: Aber notwendig.",exampleSrc:"A: Are our prices competitive?\nB: Yes, we are cheaper than the competition.\nA: Staying competitive is difficult.\nB: But necessary.",funFact:"'Wettbewerb' (competition) + 'faehig' (capable). Competitive, able to compete. 'Wettbewerbsfaehige Preise' (competitive prices). At 19 letters, a typical German compound. The Fugen-s between Wettbewerb and faehig is the glue."},

{type:"teach",trg:"boersennotiert",src:"listed on the stock exchange",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Boerse (stock exchange) + notiert (listed/noted).\nA compound participle adjective with Fugen-n.",example:"A: Ist die Firma boersennotiert?\nB: Ja, seit 2018.\nA: Was bedeutet boersennotiert genau?\nB: Die Aktien werden an der Boerse gehandelt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the company listed on the stock exchange?\nB: Yes, since 2018.\nA: What does publicly listed mean exactly?\nB: The stocks are traded on the stock exchange.",funFact:"'Boerse' (stock exchange) + 'notiert' (listed/noted). Listed on the stock exchange. 'Ein boersennotiertes Unternehmen' (a publicly listed company). The Fugen-n connects Boerse to notiert."},

{type:"teach",trg:"anlegen",src:"to invest (money)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"An (at) + legen (to lay). Separable: 'Ich lege mein Geld an.'\nOne verb, many meanings depending on context.",example:"A: Wo legen Sie Ihr Geld an?\nB: In Fonds und Immobilien.\nA: Legt man besser langfristig an?\nB: Ja, Zeit ist der beste Freund des Anlegers.",exampleSrc:"A: Where do you invest your money?\nB: In funds and real estate.\nA: Is it better to invest long-term?\nB: Yes, time is the investor's best friend.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'legen' (to lay). To invest (money), to create (a garden), to put on (clothes). 'Geld anlegen' (to invest money). Separable: 'Ich lege mein Geld an.' One verb, many meanings depending on what you lay down."},

{type:"teach",trg:"profitieren",src:"to profit, to benefit",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From French 'profiter.' Always with 'von.'\nNon-separable -ieren verb.",example:"A: Wer profitiert von niedrigen Zinsen?\nB: Alle, die einen Kredit haben.\nA: Profitieren auch Anleger?\nB: Nicht unbedingt. Sie bekommen weniger Rendite.",exampleSrc:"A: Who benefits from low interest rates?\nB: Everyone who has a loan.\nA: Do investors benefit too?\nB: Not necessarily. They get less return.",funFact:"From French 'profiter.' To profit, to benefit. 'Von etwas profitieren' (to profit from something). Always with 'von.' Non-separable -ieren verb. 'Alle profitieren von niedrigen Zinsen' (Everyone benefits from low interest rates)."},

{type:"mc",q:"Eine Rendite ist...",opts:["eine Kapitalertragsrate (return on investment)","ein Steuerabzug","ein Geschaeftskredit","ein Aktienzertifikat"],ans:"eine Kapitalertragsrate (return on investment)",hint:"The Italian banking term for what your money earns when you invest it."},

{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Aktie",src:"stock/share"},{trg:"Boerse",src:"stock exchange"},{trg:"Dividende",src:"dividend"},{trg:"Anleger",src:"investor"}]},

{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} bestimmt, wie sich Angebot und Nachfrage entwickeln.",a:["Konjunktur"],opts:["Konjunktur","Dividende","Aktie","Rendite"],hint:"The overall economic cycle that determines business conditions.",sSrc:"The economic cycle determines how supply and demand develop."},

{type:"mc",q:"Wettbewerbsfaehig bedeutet...",opts:["nachhaltig","konkurrenzfaehig (competitive)","boersennotiert","profitabel"],ans:"konkurrenzfaehig (competitive)",hint:"'Wettbewerb' is competition. 'Faehig' means capable. Capable of competing."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"amused",art:"de-ber-cafe-closing-newspaper",trg:"Ich habe gerade eine ganze Seite Boersenbericht gelesen. Vor drei Monaten haette ich kein Wort verstanden. Jetzt verstehe ich fast alles. Fast.",src:"I just read an entire page of stock market report. Three months ago I would not have understood a word. Now I understand almost everything. Almost."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l3",title:"Bis Dezember werden Sie bezahlt haben",icon:"\uD83D\uDCC5",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Bis Dezember werden Sie bezahlt haben",desc:"Learn Futur II for completed future actions and assumptions. Master tax and trade vocabulary. Understand how Germans predict financial outcomes.",goals:["Learn Futur II (werden + Partizip II + haben/sein)","Master 18 words about taxes and trade","Understand future predictions in German"]},

{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"professional",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-screen",trg:"Schauen wir auf Ihre Bilanz. Bis Dezember werden Sie Ihre Steuern bezahlt haben. Da Sie exportieren, koennen wir die Vorsteuer abziehen.",src:"Let us look at your balance sheet. By December you will have paid your taxes. Since you export, we can deduct the input tax."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"concentrating",art:"de-ber-verumius-focused",trg:"Und die Inflation? Die Preise sind stark gestiegen.",src:"And the inflation? Prices have risen sharply."},

{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"reassuring",art:"de-ber-steuerberater-calm",trg:"Die Rezession wird voraussichtlich bis Fruehjahr ueberwunden sein. Zumal die Subventionen greifen.",src:"The recession will presumably be overcome by spring. Especially since the subsidies are taking effect."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Bilanz",src:"balance sheet",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Italian 'bilancio' (balance). 'Bilanz ziehen' means\nboth a financial and philosophical expression.",example:"A: Wie sieht die Bilanz aus?\nB: Die Bilanz zeigt einen Gewinn.\nA: Wann ziehen wir Bilanz?\nB: Am Ende des Geschaeftsjahres.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the balance sheet look?\nB: The balance sheet shows a profit.\nA: When do we take stock?\nB: At the end of the fiscal year.",funFact:"From Italian 'bilancio' (balance). A balance sheet. 'Bilanz ziehen' (to take stock/draw conclusions) is both a financial and a philosophical expression. Every year, companies and individuals 'ziehen Bilanz.'"},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Export",src:"export",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'exportare' (to carry out). 'Made in Germany'\ngoods make Germany the world's third-largest exporter.",example:"A: Was ist Deutschlands wichtigster Export?\nB: Autos, Maschinen und Chemie.\nA: Wie wichtig ist der Export?\nB: Er treibt die Wirtschaft an.",exampleSrc:"A: What is Germany's most important export?\nB: Cars, machines, and chemicals.\nA: How important is export?\nB: It drives the economy.",funFact:"From Latin 'exportare' (to carry out). Export. 'Made in Germany' goods make Germany the world's third-largest exporter. Cars, machines, and chemicals are the top Exportgueter (export goods)."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Import",src:"import",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Latin 'importare' (to carry in). Germany imports\nenergy, raw materials, and food.",example:"A: Was importiert Deutschland?\nB: Viel Energie und Rohstoffe.\nA: Ist der Import gestiegen?\nB: Ja, besonders bei Energie.",exampleSrc:"A: What does Germany import?\nB: A lot of energy and raw materials.\nA: Has importing risen?\nB: Yes, especially for energy.",funFact:"From Latin 'importare' (to carry in). Import. Germany imports energy, raw materials, and food. The Handelsbilanz (trade balance) between Export and Import has been positive for decades."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Inflation",src:"inflation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'inflare' (to blow up). Germans have a deep\ncultural fear of Inflation because of 1923.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist die Inflation?\nB: Aktuell bei etwa drei Prozent.\nA: Ist das viel?\nB: Fuer deutsche Verhaeltnisse ja.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is inflation?\nB: Currently at about three percent.\nA: Is that a lot?\nB: For German standards, yes.",funFact:"From Latin 'inflare' (to blow up). Inflation. Germans have a deep cultural fear of Inflation because of 1923, when a loaf of bread cost billions of Marks. The Bundesbank was designed to prevent it ever again."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Rezession",src:"recession",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'recessio' (retreat). Two consecutive quarters\nof negative growth. The economy retreats like a tide.",example:"A: Sind wir in einer Rezession?\nB: Technisch ja. Zwei Quartale negativ.\nA: Wie lange dauert eine Rezession?\nB: Unterschiedlich. Manchmal Monate, manchmal Jahre.",exampleSrc:"A: Are we in a recession?\nB: Technically yes. Two quarters negative.\nA: How long does a recession last?\nB: It varies. Sometimes months, sometimes years.",funFact:"From Latin 'recessio' (retreat). Recession. Two consecutive quarters of negative growth. Germans call it also 'Konjunkturflaute' (economic doldrums). The economy retreats like a tide going out."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Subvention",src:"subsidy",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'subventio' (assistance). Germany spends\nbillions on Subventionen for agriculture, energy, industry.",example:"A: Bekommt die Branche Subventionen?\nB: Ja, vom Staat.\nA: Warum gibt es Subventionen?\nB: Um bestimmte Branchen zu foerdern.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the sector receive subsidies?\nB: Yes, from the state.\nA: Why are there subsidies?\nB: To support certain sectors.",funFact:"From Latin 'subventio' (assistance). A subsidy. The German government spends billions on Subventionen for agriculture, energy, and industry. 'Subventionen abbauen' (to reduce subsidies) is a perpetual political debate."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Branche",src:"industry, sector",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From French 'branche' (branch). Each branch of the\neconomic tree is a Branche.",example:"A: In welcher Branche arbeiten Sie?\nB: In der IT-Branche.\nA: Ist die Branche gewachsen?\nB: Ja, enorm in den letzten Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: What industry do you work in?\nB: In the IT sector.\nA: Has the sector grown?\nB: Yes, enormously in recent years.",funFact:"From French 'branche' (branch). An industry, a sector. 'In welcher Branche arbeiten Sie?' (What industry do you work in?). Each branch of the economic tree is a Branche."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Rohstoff",src:"raw material",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Roh (raw) + Stoff (material). Germany is poor in Rohstoffe\nbut rich in engineering.",example:"A: Welche Rohstoffe importiert Deutschland?\nB: Oel, Gas und seltene Erden.\nA: Gibt es Rohstoffmangel?\nB: In manchen Bereichen ja.",exampleSrc:"A: Which raw materials does Germany import?\nB: Oil, gas, and rare earths.\nA: Is there a shortage of raw materials?\nB: In some areas, yes.",funFact:"'Roh' (raw) + 'Stoff' (material). A raw material. Germany is poor in Rohstoffe but rich in engineering. 'Rohstoffmangel' (resource shortage) shaped Germany's industrial strategy: import raw, export finished."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Steuersatz",src:"tax rate",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Steuer (tax) + Satz (rate). Germany's top\nEinkommensteuersatz is 45%.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist Ihr Steuersatz?\nB: Bei meinem Einkommen etwa 35 Prozent.\nA: Steigt der Steuersatz mit dem Einkommen?\nB: Ja, das ist das progressive System.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is your tax rate?\nB: At my income, about 35 percent.\nA: Does the tax rate rise with income?\nB: Yes, that is the progressive system.",funFact:"'Steuer' (tax) + 'Satz' (rate). Tax rate. Germany's top Einkommensteuersatz is 45%. The progressive system means the Steuersatz rises with income. Every German knows their Steuersatz."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Lohnsteuer",src:"wage tax",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Lohn (wage) + Steuer (tax). Deducted directly from\nyour paycheck. Germans never see this money.",example:"A: Was ist Lohnsteuer?\nB: Die Steuer auf dein Gehalt.\nA: Wer zahlt die Lohnsteuer?\nB: Dein Arbeitgeber zieht sie direkt ab.",exampleSrc:"A: What is wage tax?\nB: The tax on your salary.\nA: Who pays the wage tax?\nB: Your employer deducts it directly.",funFact:"'Lohn' (wage) + 'Steuer' (tax). Wage tax, income tax on employment. Die Lohnsteuer is deducted directly from your paycheck by your employer. Germans never see this money. It vanishes before payday."},

{type:"teach",trg:"steuerpflichtig",src:"liable to tax",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Steuer (tax) + pflichtig (obligated). Everyone above\nthe Grundfreibetrag is steuerpflichtig. No exceptions.",example:"A: Bin ich in Deutschland steuerpflichtig?\nB: Ja, jeder mit Einkommen ist steuerpflichtig.\nA: Ab welchem Betrag?\nB: Ab dem Grundfreibetrag, circa 11.000 Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: Am I liable to tax in Germany?\nB: Yes, everyone with income is liable to tax.\nA: From which amount?\nB: From the basic allowance, about 11,000 euros.",funFact:"'Steuer' (tax) + 'pflichtig' (obligated). Liable to tax. Everyone earning above the Grundfreibetrag (basic tax-free allowance) in Germany is steuerpflichtig. No exceptions."},

{type:"teach",trg:"fiskalisch",src:"fiscal",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'fiscalis' (of the treasury). A formal,\ntechnical word found in economic reports.",example:"A: Welche fiskalischen Massnahmen plant die Regierung?\nB: Steuersenkungen und mehr Ausgaben.\nA: Sind fiskalische Reformen noetig?\nB: Ja, der Haushalt muss konsolidiert werden.",exampleSrc:"A: What fiscal measures does the government plan?\nB: Tax cuts and more spending.\nA: Are fiscal reforms necessary?\nB: Yes, the budget must be consolidated.",funFact:"From Latin 'fiscalis' (of the treasury). Fiscal. 'Fiskalische Massnahmen' (fiscal measures). The German Fiskus (treasury) collects taxes. A formal, technical word found in economic reports and policy papers."},

{type:"teach",trg:"konjunkturell",src:"related to the business cycle",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Konjunktur + -ell. Everything that rises and falls\nwith the economic tide is konjunkturell.",example:"A: Sind das konjunkturelle Schwankungen?\nB: Ja, die Wirtschaft schwankt zyklisch.\nA: Wie lange dauern konjunkturelle Phasen?\nB: Normalerweise fuenf bis zehn Jahre.",exampleSrc:"A: Are these cyclical fluctuations?\nB: Yes, the economy fluctuates cyclically.\nA: How long do business cycle phases last?\nB: Usually five to ten years.",funFact:"'Konjunktur' + '-ell' (adjective suffix). Related to the business cycle. 'Konjunkturelle Schwankungen' (cyclical fluctuations). Everything that rises and falls with the economic tide is konjunkturell."},

{type:"teach",trg:"exportieren",src:"to export",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'exportare.' Non-separable -ieren verb.\nSame word across European languages.",example:"A: Was exportiert Deutschland am meisten?\nB: Autos und Maschinen.\nA: Wohin exportieren wir?\nB: In die ganze Welt. China, USA, Europa.",exampleSrc:"A: What does Germany export the most?\nB: Cars and machines.\nA: Where do we export to?\nB: To the whole world. China, USA, Europe.",funFact:"From Latin 'exportare.' To export. 'Deutschland exportiert Autos in die ganze Welt' (Germany exports cars to the whole world). Non-separable -ieren verb. Same word across European languages."},

{type:"teach",trg:"importieren",src:"to import",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'importare.' The mirror verb of exportieren.\nBoth are non-separable -ieren verbs.",example:"A: Importiert Deutschland viel Energie?\nB: Ja, Oel und Gas werden importiert.\nA: Koennen wir weniger importieren?\nB: Mit erneuerbarer Energie, ja.",exampleSrc:"A: Does Germany import a lot of energy?\nB: Yes, oil and gas are imported.\nA: Can we import less?\nB: With renewable energy, yes.",funFact:"From Latin 'importare.' To import. 'Rohstoffe importieren' (to import raw materials). The mirror verb of exportieren. Both are non-separable -ieren verbs."},

{type:"teach",trg:"besteuern",src:"to tax",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Be- + steuern (to tax/steer). The be- prefix makes it\ntransitive. Not separable.",example:"A: Wie wird Einkommen besteuert?\nB: Progressiv. Je mehr, desto hoeher der Satz.\nA: Werden auch Renten besteuert?\nB: Ja, teilweise.",exampleSrc:"A: How is income taxed?\nB: Progressively. The more, the higher the rate.\nA: Are pensions also taxed?\nB: Yes, partially.",funFact:"'Be-' + 'steuern' (to tax/steer). To tax. 'Einkommen besteuern' (to tax income). The be- prefix makes it transitive. Not separable. 'Hoch besteuert' (heavily taxed) describes most things in Germany."},

{type:"teach",trg:"einsparen",src:"to save, to cut costs",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Ein (in) + sparen (to save). Separable: 'Wir sparen 20% ein.'\nMore specific than 'sparen': reducing from a previous level.",example:"A: Koennen wir Kosten einsparen?\nB: Ja, beim Material sparen wir 15% ein.\nA: Wo noch?\nB: Bei den Energiekosten.",exampleSrc:"A: Can we cut costs?\nB: Yes, on materials we save 15%.\nA: Where else?\nB: On energy costs.",funFact:"'Ein' (in) + 'sparen' (to save). To save, to cut costs. 'Kosten einsparen' (to cut costs). Separable: 'Wir sparen 20% ein.' More specific than just 'sparen': einsparen implies reducing from a previous level."},

{type:"teach",trg:"voraussichtlich",src:"presumably, expected",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Voraus (ahead) + sichtlich (visibly). A hedging word\nthat financial analysts use constantly.",example:"A: Wann wird die Wirtschaft wachsen?\nB: Voraussichtlich im naechsten Quartal.\nA: Ist das sicher?\nB: Nein, voraussichtlich heisst 'wahrscheinlich.'",exampleSrc:"A: When will the economy grow?\nB: Presumably in the next quarter.\nA: Is that certain?\nB: No, voraussichtlich means 'probably.'",funFact:"'Voraus' (ahead) + 'sichtlich' (visibly). Presumably, expected. 'Voraussichtlich wird die Wirtschaft wachsen' (The economy is expected to grow). A hedging word that financial analysts use constantly. Never commit, always qualify."},

{type:"tip",title:"Futur II: Das vollendete Futur",text:"German has a tense for actions that will be completed in the future.\n\nFormation: werden + Partizip II + haben/sein\n\nExamples:\n- Bis Dezember werde ich die Steuern bezahlt haben.\n- Die Rezession wird bis Fruehjahr ueberwunden sein.\n\nTwo uses:\n1. Completed future: 'Bis morgen werde ich alles erledigt haben.'\n2. Assumption about the past: 'Er wird wohl schon gegangen sein.' (He has probably already left.)\n\nHaben or sein? Same rule as the Perfekt:\n- haben: most verbs (bezahlt haben, geschrieben haben)\n- sein: movement and change-of-state verbs (gegangen sein, gestiegen sein)",deepDive:{title:"Futur II: formation and usage",text:"The Futur II is formed with werden + Partizip II + haben/sein. It describes an action that will be completed by a future point, or expresses a probability judgment about the past.\n\nThe auxiliary (haben or sein) follows the same rules as the Perfekt:\n- haben: most transitive verbs, reflexive verbs\n- sein: movement verbs (gehen, kommen, fliegen), change-of-state verbs (sterben, wachsen, steigen), sein and bleiben\n\nWord order: werden is conjugated and in position 2. The Partizip II and haben/sein go to the end.\n- Hauptsatz: Er wird die Steuern bezahlt haben.\n- Nebensatz: ..., weil er die Steuern bezahlt haben wird.\n\nWith 'wohl' or 'wahrscheinlich,' Futur II expresses assumption:\n- Er wird wohl krank gewesen sein. (He was probably sick.)"}},

{type:"verb_table",title:"Futur II: werden + Partizip II + haben/sein",groups:[{label:"Formation with haben",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"werde ... bezahlt haben",src:"I will have paid"},{pronoun:"du",form:"wirst ... bezahlt haben",src:"you will have paid"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wird ... bezahlt haben",src:"he/she/it will have paid"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"werden ... bezahlt haben",src:"we will have paid"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"werdet ... bezahlt haben",src:"you all will have paid"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"werden ... bezahlt haben",src:"they/you will have paid"}]},{label:"Formation with sein (Bewegungs-/Zustandsverben)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"werde ... gestiegen sein",src:"I will have risen"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"wird ... gewachsen sein",src:"he/she/it will have grown"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"werden ... angekommen sein",src:"we will have arrived"}]}]},

{type:"mc",q:"Der Steuerberater sagt: 'Bis Jahresende werden Sie die Rueckerstattung erhalten haben.' Welches Tempus ist das?",opts:["Perfekt","Futur II","Plusquamperfekt","Futur I"],ans:"Futur II",hint:"werden + Partizip II + haben. An action that will be completed by a specific point in time."},

{type:"fb",s:"Die Inflation wird bis Fruehjahr {1} sein.",a:["gesunken"],opts:["gesunken","sinken","gesinkt","sank"],hint:"'Sinken' uses 'sein' in the Perfekt. Futur II: werden + Partizip II + sein.",sSrc:"Inflation will have fallen by spring."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"determined",art:"de-ber-verumius-notes",trg:"Bis Dezember werde ich die Steuererklaerung abgegeben haben. Das hat der Steuerberater versprochen. Und ich habe es zur Kenntnis genommen.",src:"By December I will have submitted the tax return. The tax advisor promised that. And I have taken note of it."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l4",title:"Da die Wirtschaft waechst",icon:"\uD83D\uDCC8",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Da die Wirtschaft waechst",desc:"Master advanced causal connectors beyond weil and denn. Analyze economic cause-and-effect relationships. Build complex argumentative sentences.",goals:["Learn causal clauses with da, zumal, umso mehr als, insofern als","Master 18 words about macroeconomics and business cycles","Translate economic relationships into complex sentences"]},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Insolvenz",src:"insolvency",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"From Latin 'insolventia' (inability to pay). 'Insolvenz\nanmelden' is a formal legal step.",example:"A: Hat die Firma Insolvenz angemeldet?\nB: Ja, letzte Woche.\nA: Was passiert bei einer Insolvenz?\nB: Ein Insolvenzverwalter uebernimmt.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company file for insolvency?\nB: Yes, last week.\nA: What happens during an insolvency?\nB: An insolvency administrator takes over.",funFact:"From Latin 'insolventia' (inability to pay). Insolvency. 'Insolvenz anmelden' (to file for insolvency) is a formal legal step. Germany reformed its Insolvenzrecht (insolvency law) to give debtors a second chance after six years."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Bankrott",src:"bankruptcy",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"From Italian 'banca rotta' (broken bench). Medieval money\nchangers worked at benches. Broken bench = bankruptcy.",example:"A: Die Firma ist bankrott.\nB: Bankrott? Das ist das Ende.\nA: Was ist der Unterschied zur Insolvenz?\nB: Bankrott ist endgueltig. Insolvenz kann man ueberleben.",exampleSrc:"A: The company is bankrupt.\nB: Bankrupt? That is the end.\nA: What is the difference from insolvency?\nB: Bankruptcy is final. Insolvency can be survived.",funFact:"From Italian 'banca rotta' (broken bench). Medieval Italian money changers worked at benches. When they could not pay, the bench was broken. The broken bench became bankruptcy."},

{type:"teach",trg:"das Wachstum",src:"growth",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From 'wachsen' (to grow) + '-tum.' The -tum ending\nalways creates neuter nouns: Eigentum, Altertum.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist das Wirtschaftswachstum?\nB: Etwa 1,5 Prozent.\nA: Ist das genug Wachstum?\nB: Fuer Deutschland ist das solide.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is economic growth?\nB: About 1.5 percent.\nA: Is that enough growth?\nB: For Germany, that is solid.",funFact:"From 'wachsen' (to grow) + '-tum' (state/condition). Growth. 'Wirtschaftswachstum' (economic growth) is the metric politicians celebrate. The -tum ending always creates neuter nouns: Eigentum, Altertum, Wachstum."},

{type:"teach",trg:"der Aufschwung",src:"upswing, boom",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Auf (up) + Schwung (swing/momentum). The recovery\nphase of the business cycle. The economy swings upward.",example:"A: Kommt bald ein Aufschwung?\nB: Die Experten sagen ja.\nA: Wie erkennt man einen Aufschwung?\nB: Mehr Auftraege, weniger Arbeitslose.",exampleSrc:"A: Is an upswing coming soon?\nB: The experts say yes.\nA: How do you recognize an upswing?\nB: More orders, fewer unemployed.",funFact:"'Auf' (up) + 'Schwung' (swing/momentum). An upswing, a boom. 'Wirtschaftlicher Aufschwung' describes the recovery phase of the business cycle. The economy swings upward."},

{type:"teach",trg:"das Konjunkturpaket",src:"stimulus package",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Konjunktur + Paket. Governments deploy these during\nrecessions. Germany's 2020 package was 130 billion euros.",example:"A: Was ist ein Konjunkturpaket?\nB: Geld vom Staat, um die Wirtschaft anzukurbeln.\nA: Funktionieren Konjunkturpakete?\nB: Meistens ja, aber sie kosten viel.",exampleSrc:"A: What is a stimulus package?\nB: Money from the state to boost the economy.\nA: Do stimulus packages work?\nB: Usually yes, but they cost a lot.",funFact:"'Konjunktur' (economic cycle) + 'Paket' (package). A stimulus package. Governments deploy these during recessions. Germany's 2020 Konjunkturpaket was 130 billion euros. A package to restart the economic engine."},

{type:"teach",trg:"das Defizit",src:"deficit",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"From Latin 'deficit' (it is lacking). Germany's Schuldenbremse\nin the constitution limits the federal Defizit.",example:"A: Hat der Haushalt ein Defizit?\nB: Ja, die Ausgaben uebersteigen die Einnahmen.\nA: Wie gross ist das Defizit?\nB: Mehrere Milliarden Euro.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the budget have a deficit?\nB: Yes, spending exceeds revenue.\nA: How large is the deficit?\nB: Several billion euros.",funFact:"From Latin 'deficit' (it is lacking). A deficit. 'Haushaltsdefizit' (budget deficit). Germany's Schuldenbremse (debt brake) in the constitution limits the federal Defizit. No other country constitutionally bans deficits."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Handelsbilanz",src:"trade balance",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Handel (trade) + Bilanz (balance). The difference between\nexports and imports. Germany's is typically positive.",example:"A: Wie sieht die Handelsbilanz aus?\nB: Positiv. Wir exportieren mehr als wir importieren.\nA: Ist eine positive Handelsbilanz immer gut?\nB: Meistens, aber es gibt Kritik.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the trade balance look?\nB: Positive. We export more than we import.\nA: Is a positive trade balance always good?\nB: Usually, but there is criticism.",funFact:"'Handel' (trade) + 'Bilanz' (balance). Trade balance. The difference between exports and imports. Germany's Handelsbilanz is typically positive: more goes out than comes in."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Volkswirtschaft",src:"national economy, macroeconomics",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Volk (people) + Wirtschaft (economy). 'VWL' is the study\nof entire economies. Contrast: BWL studies companies.",example:"A: Was ist Volkswirtschaft?\nB: Die Wirtschaft eines ganzen Landes.\nA: Und Betriebswirtschaft?\nB: Die Wirtschaft einzelner Unternehmen.",exampleSrc:"A: What is Volkswirtschaft?\nB: The economy of an entire country.\nA: And Betriebswirtschaft?\nB: The economics of individual companies.",funFact:"'Volk' (people) + 'Wirtschaft' (economy). National economy, macroeconomics. 'Volkswirtschaftslehre' (VWL) is the study of entire economies. Contrast: Betriebswirtschaft (BWL) studies individual companies."},

{type:"teach",trg:"die Globalisierung",src:"globalization",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Global + -isierung (process suffix). The -ung ending\nmakes it feminine.",example:"A: Wie beeinflusst die Globalisierung Deutschland?\nB: Durch mehr Handel und Wettbewerb.\nA: Gibt es Kritik an der Globalisierung?\nB: Ja, besonders von Gewerkschaften.",exampleSrc:"A: How does globalization affect Germany?\nB: Through more trade and competition.\nA: Is there criticism of globalization?\nB: Yes, especially from trade unions.",funFact:"'Global' + '-isierung' (process suffix). Globalization. Germany is one of the most globalized economies on Earth. The -ung ending makes it feminine. 'Globalisierungskritiker' (critics of globalization) are loud in Germany."},

{type:"teach",trg:"defizitaer",src:"operating at a deficit",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Defizit + -aer. The -aer ending comes from French\nand always signals an adjective describing a state.",example:"A: Ist der Haushalt defizitaer?\nB: Ja, wir geben mehr aus als wir einnehmen.\nA: Wie lange kann man defizitaer wirtschaften?\nB: Nicht ewig. Irgendwann kommen die Schulden.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the budget in deficit?\nB: Yes, we spend more than we take in.\nA: How long can you run a deficit?\nB: Not forever. Eventually the debts come.",funFact:"'Defizit' + '-aer' (adjective suffix). Operating at a deficit. 'Ein defizitaerer Haushalt' (a deficit budget). The -aer ending comes from French and always signals an adjective describing a state."},

{type:"teach",trg:"marktwirtschaftlich",src:"relating to the market economy",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Marktwirtschaft (market economy) + -lich. Germany calls\nits system 'soziale Marktwirtschaft.'",example:"A: Ist Deutschland marktwirtschaftlich?\nB: Ja, aber mit sozialer Absicherung.\nA: Was sind marktwirtschaftliche Prinzipien?\nB: Freier Wettbewerb und Privatbesitz.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Germany a market economy?\nB: Yes, but with social security.\nA: What are market economy principles?\nB: Free competition and private ownership.",funFact:"'Marktwirtschaft' (market economy) + '-lich.' Relating to the market economy. 'Marktwirtschaftliche Prinzipien' (market economy principles). Germany calls its system 'soziale Marktwirtschaft' (social market economy): capitalism with a safety net."},

{type:"teach",trg:"volkswirtschaftlich",src:"macroeconomic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Volkswirtschaft + -lich. GDP, inflation, unemployment\nare volkswirtschaftliche Indikatoren.",example:"A: Was sind volkswirtschaftliche Daten?\nB: BIP, Inflation, Arbeitslosenquote.\nA: Warum sind sie wichtig?\nB: Sie zeigen den Zustand der Wirtschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: What is macroeconomic data?\nB: GDP, inflation, unemployment rate.\nA: Why is it important?\nB: It shows the state of the economy.",funFact:"'Volkswirtschaft' + '-lich.' Macroeconomic. 'Volkswirtschaftliche Daten' (macroeconomic data). The adjectival form of the national economy. GDP, inflation, unemployment are volkswirtschaftliche Indikatoren."},

{type:"teach",trg:"betriebswirtschaftlich",src:"relating to business economics",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Betriebswirtschaft (business administration) + -lich.\nThe micro-level counterpart to volkswirtschaftlich.",example:"A: Was sind betriebswirtschaftliche Kennzahlen?\nB: Umsatz, Gewinn, Kosten pro Einheit.\nA: Und volkswirtschaftliche?\nB: BIP, Handelsbilanz, Inflation.",exampleSrc:"A: What are business metrics?\nB: Revenue, profit, cost per unit.\nA: And macroeconomic ones?\nB: GDP, trade balance, inflation.",funFact:"'Betriebswirtschaft' (business administration) + '-lich.' Relating to business economics. 'Betriebswirtschaftliche Kennzahlen' (business metrics). The micro-level counterpart to volkswirtschaftlich."},

{type:"teach",trg:"konkurrieren",src:"to compete",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'concurrere' (to run together).\nNon-separable -ieren verb. Originally: running the same race.",example:"A: Konkurriert Ihre Firma mit Siemens?\nB: Ja, wir konkurrieren um die gleichen Kunden.\nA: Ist es schwer, mit Grosskonzernen zu konkurrieren?\nB: Ja, aber wir sind flexibler.",exampleSrc:"A: Does your company compete with Siemens?\nB: Yes, we compete for the same clients.\nA: Is it hard to compete with large corporations?\nB: Yes, but we are more flexible.",funFact:"From Latin 'concurrere' (to run together). To compete. 'Mit jemandem konkurrieren' (to compete with someone). Non-separable -ieren verb. Originally: running the same race."},

{type:"teach",trg:"sanieren",src:"to restructure, to renovate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'sanare' (to heal). Healing a sick business.\nAlso used for buildings.",example:"A: Muss die Firma saniert werden?\nB: Ja, die Finanzen sind kritisch.\nA: Wie saniert man ein Unternehmen?\nB: Kosten senken, Schulden reduzieren, neu aufstellen.",exampleSrc:"A: Does the company need to be restructured?\nB: Yes, the finances are critical.\nA: How do you restructure a company?\nB: Cut costs, reduce debts, reposition.",funFact:"From Latin 'sanare' (to heal). To restructure, to renovate. 'Ein Unternehmen sanieren' (to restructure a company). Healing a sick business. Also used for buildings: 'ein Gebaede sanieren' (to renovate a building)."},

{type:"teach",trg:"konsolidieren",src:"to consolidate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'consolidare' (to make firm). Making something\nsolid that was shaky. Standard political-economic vocabulary.",example:"A: Muessen wir den Haushalt konsolidieren?\nB: Ja, die Schulden sind zu hoch.\nA: Wie konsolidiert man einen Haushalt?\nB: Weniger ausgeben, mehr einnehmen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do we need to consolidate the budget?\nB: Yes, the debts are too high.\nA: How do you consolidate a budget?\nB: Spend less, earn more.",funFact:"From Latin 'consolidare' (to make firm). To consolidate. 'Den Haushalt konsolidieren' (to consolidate the budget). Making something solid that was shaky. Standard political-economic vocabulary."},

{type:"teach",trg:"spekulieren",src:"to speculate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From Latin 'speculari' (to observe). Originally:\nwatching from a watchtower. Now: bets on the future.",example:"A: Spekulierst du an der Boerse?\nB: Nein, das ist mir zu riskant.\nA: Viele spekulieren mit Kryptowaehrungen.\nB: Ja, aber Spekulation ist kein Investieren.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you speculate on the stock market?\nB: No, that is too risky for me.\nA: Many speculate with cryptocurrencies.\nB: Yes, but speculation is not investing.",funFact:"From Latin 'speculari' (to observe). To speculate. 'An der Boerse spekulieren' (to speculate on the stock market). Originally: watching from a watchtower. Now: making bets on the future."},

{type:"teach",trg:"schaetzungsweise",src:"approximately, by estimation",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Schaetzung (estimate) + -weise (manner). A hedging adverb\nlike voraussichtlich. German financial language loves qualifiers.",example:"A: Wie viele Jobs gehen verloren?\nB: Schaetzungsweise 10.000.\nA: Ist das sicher?\nB: Nein, schaetzungsweise heisst 'ungefaehr.'",exampleSrc:"A: How many jobs will be lost?\nB: Approximately 10,000.\nA: Is that certain?\nB: No, schaetzungsweise means 'approximately.'",funFact:"'Schaetzung' (estimate) + '-weise' (manner). Approximately, by estimation. 'Schaetzungsweise 50 Milliarden Euro' (approximately 50 billion euros). A hedging adverb like voraussichtlich. German financial language loves qualifiers."},

{type:"tip",title:"Kausalsaetze: Jenseits von weil und denn",text:"At B2 level you need more than weil and denn for cause and effect.\n\nNew connectors, sorted by formality:\n- da (since/because): 'Da die Wirtschaft waechst, steigen die Einnahmen.' Formal, written. Verb at the end.\n- zumal (especially since): 'Die Investition lohnt sich, zumal die Zinsen niedrig sind.' Emphasizes the reason.\n- umso mehr als (all the more since): 'Das ist wichtig, umso mehr als die Konkurrenz waechst.'\n- insofern als (insofar as): 'Das stimmt, insofern als die Daten korrekt sind.' Academic.\n- in Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass: Bureaucratic. Very formal.\n- naemlich (you see, because): 'Er investiert, er hat naemlich Kapital.' AFTER the verb.\n- und zwar (specifically): 'Wir sparen, und zwar 20%.' Specifies.\n\nAll create subordinate clauses with verb at the end, except naemlich and und zwar.",deepDive:{title:"Advanced causal connectors: complete guide",text:"Da vs. weil: Both mean 'because/since,' but da is more formal and common in written German. Da-clauses usually come first in the sentence. Weil-clauses usually come second.\n\nZumal: 'Especially since.' Adds weight to a reason. Always comes after the main clause: '..., zumal die Zinsen niedrig sind.'\n\nUmso mehr als: 'All the more since.' Strongest emphasis on the cause. Written, formal.\n\nInsofern als: 'Insofar as.' Limits the scope of a claim. Academic precision.\n\nIn Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass: 'In view of the fact that.' Seven words to say 'because.' Maximum bureaucratic formality.\n\nNaemlich: Post-verbal. Main clause word order. 'Er spart; er hat naemlich Schulden.' Explains after the fact.\n\nUnd zwar: Specifies. 'Wir investieren, und zwar in Aktien.' Introduces the detail."}},

{type:"verb_table",title:"Kausalsaetze: Konnektoren und Wortstellung",groups:[{label:"Nebensatz-Konnektoren (Verb am Ende)",rows:[{pronoun:"da",form:"Da er investiert, waechst sein Kapital.",src:"Since he invests, his capital grows."},{pronoun:"zumal",form:"..., zumal die Zinsen niedrig sind.",src:"..., especially since interest rates are low."},{pronoun:"umso mehr als",form:"..., umso mehr als die Nachfrage steigt.",src:"..., all the more since demand rises."},{pronoun:"insofern als",form:"..., insofern als die Daten stimmen.",src:"..., insofar as the data is correct."}]},{label:"Adverbiale Konnektoren (Hauptsatz-Wortstellung)",rows:[{pronoun:"naemlich",form:"Er spart; er hat naemlich Schulden.",src:"He saves; he has debts, you see."},{pronoun:"und zwar",form:"Wir investieren, und zwar in Aktien.",src:"We invest, namely in stocks."},{pronoun:"schliesslich",form:"Er arbeitet hart; schliesslich hat er Schulden.",src:"He works hard; after all, he has debts."}]}]},

{type:"mc",q:"'Die Investition lohnt sich, zumal die Zinsen niedrig sind.' Was bewirkt 'zumal' hier?",opts:["Es widerspricht der Ursache","Es betont die Ursache (besonders weil)","Es schwaecht die Ursache ab","Es stellt die Ursache in Frage"],ans:"Es betont die Ursache (besonders weil)",hint:"'Zumal' strengthens the statement. Not simply 'weil' (because), but 'especially because.'"},

{type:"fb",s:"{1} die Exporte steigen, waechst der Umsatz.",a:["Da"],opts:["Da","Weil","Denn","Aber"],hint:"The formal connector for 'since/as.' Two letters. Typical of elevated written German.",sSrc:"Since exports are rising, revenue is growing."},

{type:"mc",q:"'Bis 2030 wird Deutschland seine Klimaziele erreicht haben.' Dieser Satz benutzt Futur II, um auszudruecken...",opts:["einen Befehl","einen aktuellen Zustand","eine abgeschlossene zukuenftige Handlung","ein vergangenes Ereignis"],ans:"eine abgeschlossene zukuenftige Handlung",hint:"werden + Partizip II + haben. Something that will be completed by a specific date."},

{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} die Regierung Subventionen gibt, wird die Branche sich bis 2025 {2} haben.",blanks:{"1":"Da","2":"erholt"},pool:["Da","erholt","Weil","erholen","Denn","erholte"],hint:"Formal causal clause + Futur II. Gap 1: written connector (two letters). Gap 2: Partizip II of 'sich erholen.'",sSrc:"Since the government gives subsidies, the sector will have recovered by 2025."},

{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Wachstum",src:"growth"},{trg:"Rezession",src:"recession"},{trg:"Aufschwung",src:"upswing"},{trg:"Insolvenz",src:"insolvency"}]}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l5",title:"Eine Entscheidung treffen",icon:"\uD83E\uDD1D",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Eine Entscheidung treffen",desc:"Fixed noun-verb combinations are the secret of formal German. The tax advisor finishes his consultation, and Mia talks about Elterngeld. Learn six collocations every professional knows.",goals:["Master fixed noun-verb combinations in formal context","Understand Germany's social benefits system","Practice all three grammar constructions together"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"steuerberater",mood:"concluding",art:"de-ber-tax-office",trg:"So, Herr Verumius. Wir muessen eine Entscheidung treffen. Ziehen Sie die Kleinunternehmerregelung in Betracht, oder wollen Sie die volle Umsatzsteuer?",src:"So, Mr. Verumius. We need to make a decision. Are you considering the small business regulation, or do you want the full sales tax?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thinking",art:"de-ber-tax-office-thinking",trg:"Ich muss das in Betracht ziehen. Was steht mir zur Verfuegung?",src:"I need to consider that. What is available to me?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"transitional",art:"de-ber-park-autumn",trg:"Spaeter am Nachmittag. Ein Berliner Park im Herbst. Mia und Verumius gehen zusammen spazieren. Das Gespraech wird persoenlich: Mia denkt ueber Elterngeld nach.",src:"Later that afternoon. A Berlin park in autumn. Mia and Verumius walk together. The conversation turns personal: Mia is thinking about parental benefit."},
{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-park-mia",trg:"Ich muss eine Entscheidung treffen. Elterngeld oder Karriere. Oder beides. Deutschland stellt beides zur Verfuegung, aber man muss es auch in Kauf nehmen, dass sich alles veraendert.",src:"I need to make a decision. Parental benefit or career. Or both. Germany makes both available, but you also have to accept that everything changes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Privatisierung",src:"privatization",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Privat + -isierung.\n'Die Privatisierung der Deutschen Post.'",example:"A: Die Privatisierung war umstritten.\nB: Welche Privatisierung meinst du?\nA: Die der Deutschen Bahn.\nB: Ja, darueber wird bis heute diskutiert.",exampleSrc:"A: The privatization was controversial.\nB: Which privatization do you mean?\nA: That of the Deutsche Bahn.\nB: Yes, it is still debated today.",funFact:"After reunification in 1990, the Treuhandanstalt privatized 8,000 East German state companies. The largest privatization program in history reshaped Germany's economy overnight."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Bruttoinlandsprodukt",src:"gross domestic product (GDP)",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Brutto + Inland + Produkt.\nAbbreviated: BIP. Das BIP Deutschlands.",example:"A: Wie hoch ist das Bruttoinlandsprodukt?\nB: Das BIP liegt bei ueber 4 Billionen Euro.\nA: Damit ist Deutschland die groesste Volkswirtschaft in Europa.\nB: Und die viertgroesste weltweit.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is the gross domestic product?\nB: GDP is over 4 trillion euros.\nA: That makes Germany the largest economy in Europe.\nB: And the fourth largest worldwide.",funFact:"At 25 letters, Bruttoinlandsprodukt is a workout. Everyone says BIP (pronounced like 'bipp'). Germany has the fourth-largest BIP in the world after the USA, China, and Japan."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Sozialleistung",src:"social benefit",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Sozial + Leistung (benefit).\nPlural: Sozialleistungen.",example:"A: Welche Sozialleistungen gibt es in Deutschland?\nB: Kindergeld, Elterngeld, Arbeitslosengeld, Wohngeld.\nA: Das ist ein umfangreiches System.\nB: Ja, die Sozialleistungen kosten ueber 30% des BIP.",exampleSrc:"A: What social benefits exist in Germany?\nB: Child benefit, parental benefit, unemployment benefit, housing benefit.\nA: That is an extensive system.\nB: Yes, social benefits cost over 30% of GDP.",funFact:"Kindergeld, Elterngeld, Arbeitslosengeld, Wohngeld, Buergergeld: Germany's social safety net is built from dozens of Sozialleistungen. The system costs more than any military budget."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Nettogehalt",src:"net salary, take-home pay",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Netto + Gehalt.\n'Mein Nettogehalt ist deutlich weniger als mein Bruttolohn.'",example:"A: Was ist dein Nettogehalt?\nB: Etwa 2.800 Euro.\nA: Und dein Bruttolohn?\nB: 4.500. Die Differenz ist schmerzhaft.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your net salary?\nB: About 2,800 euros.\nA: And your gross wage?\nB: 4,500. The difference is painful.",funFact:"What arrives in your bank account. Typically 55-65% of your Bruttolohn. The gap between Brutto and Netto shocks every newcomer to Germany. Taxes plus social contributions devour the rest."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Bruttolohn",src:"gross wage",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Brutto + Lohn.\n'Der Bruttolohn steht im Arbeitsvertrag.'",example:"A: Mein Bruttolohn betraegt 5.000 Euro.\nB: Und wie viel kommt netto an?\nA: Ungefaehr 3.100.\nB: Fast 40% Abzuege. Willkommen in Deutschland.",exampleSrc:"A: My gross wage is 5,000 euros.\nB: And how much arrives net?\nA: Approximately 3,100.\nB: Almost 40% deductions. Welcome to Germany.",funFact:"The number you negotiate but never see. Before Lohnsteuer, Sozialabgaben, and Krankenversicherung eat their share. The Bruttolohn is a promise; the Nettogehalt is reality."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Einzelhandel",src:"retail trade",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Einzel + Handel.\n'Im Einzelhandel arbeiten' (to work in retail).",example:"A: Der Einzelhandel hat sich veraendert.\nB: Inwiefern?\nA: Mehr Online-Handel, weniger Ladengeschaefte.\nB: Trotzdem bleibt der Einzelhandel wichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: Retail trade has changed.\nB: In what way?\nA: More online trade, fewer physical stores.\nB: Nevertheless, retail remains important.",funFact:"Germany's Einzelhandel includes ALDI, LIDL, and REWE, all global retail giants born in Germany. Despite the rise of online shopping, German city centers still fight to keep their Einzelhandel alive."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Grosshandel",src:"wholesale trade",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Gross + Handel.\n'Der Grosshandel liefert an den Einzelhandel.'",example:"A: Im Grosshandel kauft man in grossen Mengen.\nB: Fuer wen ist der Grosshandel gedacht?\nA: Fuer Unternehmen, nicht fuer Endkunden.\nB: Also Business-to-Business.",exampleSrc:"A: In wholesale, you buy in large quantities.\nB: Who is wholesale intended for?\nA: For businesses, not for end customers.\nB: So business-to-business.",funFact:"Buying and selling in bulk. Metro AG is Germany's largest Grosshandel company. You need a business card to shop there. Selling to businesses, not consumers."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Aussenhandel",src:"foreign trade",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Aussen + Handel.\n'Der Aussenhandel ist stark.'",example:"A: Deutschlands Aussenhandel ist einer der staerksten weltweit.\nB: Was exportiert Deutschland vor allem?\nA: Autos, Maschinen und Chemie.\nB: Und was wird importiert?\nA: Energie und Rohstoffe.",exampleSrc:"A: Germany's foreign trade is one of the strongest worldwide.\nB: What does Germany mainly export?\nA: Cars, machines, and chemicals.\nB: And what is imported?\nA: Energy and raw materials.",funFact:"Germany's Aussenhandel is one of the strongest in the world. The Aussenhandelsbilanz (foreign trade balance) has been positive for decades: more goes out than comes in."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eine Entscheidung treffen",src:"to make a decision",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Entscheidung + treffen.\nFormal register. Not 'machen.'",example:"A: Wir muessen eine Entscheidung treffen.\nB: Ueber welches Thema?\nA: Eine wichtige geschaeftliche Entscheidung.\nB: Dann treffen wir sie gemeinsam.",exampleSrc:"A: We need to make a decision.\nB: About which topic?\nA: An important business decision.\nB: Then let us make it together.",funFact:"You do not 'machen' a decision in formal German. You 'treffen' it, as if aiming at the right target. Entscheidung always pairs with treffen in business and legal contexts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Betracht ziehen",src:"to take into consideration",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Betracht + ziehen.\n'Alle Optionen in Betracht ziehen.'",example:"A: Haben Sie alle Optionen in Betracht gezogen?\nB: Ja, wir haben alles in Betracht gezogen.\nA: Auch die guenstigere Alternative?\nB: Die ziehen wir ebenfalls in Betracht.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you considered all options?\nB: Yes, we have considered everything.\nA: Also the cheaper alternative?\nB: We are considering that as well.",funFact:"You pull something into your field of view. Formal, essential in business and legal writing. The Partizip II form 'in Betracht gezogen' appears in every board meeting."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zur Verfuegung stehen",src:"to be available",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Verfuegung + stehen.\n'Ich stehe Ihnen jederzeit zur Verfuegung.'",example:"A: Welche Mittel stehen zur Verfuegung?\nB: Es stehen 50.000 Euro zur Verfuegung.\nA: Stehen auch Berater zur Verfuegung?\nB: Ja, ich stehe Ihnen jederzeit zur Verfuegung.",exampleSrc:"A: What funds are available?\nB: 50,000 euros are available.\nA: Are advisors also available?\nB: Yes, I am available to you at any time.",funFact:"'Ich stehe Ihnen jederzeit zur Verfuegung' is the gold standard of formal German politeness. Literally: I stand at your disposal. The perfect closing line for business emails."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Einfluss nehmen auf",src:"to exert influence on",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Einfluss + nehmen + auf.\n'Die Regierung nimmt Einfluss auf die Wirtschaft.'",example:"A: Wer nimmt Einfluss auf die Entscheidung?\nB: Die Aktionaere nehmen grossen Einfluss.\nA: Kann die Regierung auch Einfluss nehmen?\nB: Ja, sie nimmt durch Gesetze Einfluss auf den Markt.",exampleSrc:"A: Who exerts influence on the decision?\nB: The shareholders exert great influence.\nA: Can the government also exert influence?\nB: Yes, it exerts influence on the market through laws.",funFact:"You take influence upon something. More deliberate than simply 'beeinflussen.' In political and economic contexts, Einfluss nehmen implies strategic, purposeful action."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Kauf nehmen",src:"to accept (a drawback)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Kauf + nehmen.\n'Ich nehme die Nachteile in Kauf.'",example:"A: Man muss gewisse Risiken in Kauf nehmen.\nB: Welche Risiken zum Beispiel?\nA: Verluste. Die muss man in Kauf nehmen.\nB: Ohne Risiko kein Gewinn.",exampleSrc:"A: You have to accept certain risks.\nB: Which risks, for example?\nA: Losses. You have to accept those.\nB: No risk, no reward.",funFact:"You take something negative into the deal. You accept a drawback as part of a larger bargain. 'Ich nehme die Nachteile in Kauf' means: I know the downsides, and I accept them anyway."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einen Beitrag leisten",src:"to make a contribution",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Beitrag + leisten.\n'Jeder kann einen Beitrag leisten.'",example:"A: Jeder sollte einen Beitrag leisten.\nB: Welchen Beitrag meinst du?\nA: Einen finanziellen Beitrag zum Projekt.\nB: Ich leiste gerne meinen Beitrag.",exampleSrc:"A: Everyone should make a contribution.\nB: What kind of contribution do you mean?\nA: A financial contribution to the project.\nB: I am happy to make my contribution.",funFact:"You perform a contribution. Formal and positive. The civic-minded way to say 'help out.' Politicians love this phrase: 'Jeder muss seinen Beitrag leisten.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"absetzen",src:"to deduct (from taxes), to sell, to remove",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ab + setzen.\n'Kosten von der Steuer absetzen.'",example:"A: Kann ich das von der Steuer absetzen?\nB: Ja, Geschaeftsausgaben setzen Sie ab.\nA: Auch das Homeoffice?\nB: Bis zu 1.260 Euro im Jahr setzen Sie ab.",exampleSrc:"A: Can I deduct that from taxes?\nB: Yes, you deduct business expenses.\nA: Also the home office?\nB: You deduct up to 1,260 euros per year.",funFact:"Three distinct meanings depending on context: deduct from taxes, sell goods, or remove someone from office. 'Von der Steuer absetzen' is every German freelancer's favorite phrase."},
{type:"teach",trg:"umsetzen",src:"to implement, to generate revenue",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Um + setzen.\n'Einen Plan umsetzen' (to implement a plan).",example:"A: Wie setzen wir den Plan um?\nB: Schritt fuer Schritt.\nA: Das Unternehmen setzt jaehrlich 2 Millionen um.\nB: Beeindruckend. Gut umgesetzt.",exampleSrc:"A: How do we implement the plan?\nB: Step by step.\nA: The company generates 2 million in revenue annually.\nB: Impressive. Well implemented.",funFact:"Separable verb with two meanings: implement a plan or generate revenue. 'Millionen umsetzen' means generating millions in turnover. The verb of action in business contexts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"privatisieren",src:"to privatize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Staatliche Betriebe privatisieren.'",example:"A: Soll man die Deutsche Bahn privatisieren?\nB: Darueber wird lange diskutiert.\nA: England hat seine Eisenbahn privatisiert.\nB: Mit gemischten Ergebnissen.",exampleSrc:"A: Should the Deutsche Bahn be privatized?\nB: That has been debated for a long time.\nA: England privatized its railway.\nB: With mixed results.",funFact:"The opposite of verstaatlichen (to nationalize). Germany has done both at different points in history. The Treuhandanstalt privatized an entire country's economy after 1990."},
{type:"teach",trg:"monatlich",src:"monthly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Monat + -lich. Adverb and adjective.\n'Monatliche Kosten' (monthly costs).",example:"A: Die monatlichen Kosten betragen 500 Euro.\nB: Wird monatlich abgebucht?\nA: Ja, die Abbuchung erfolgt monatlich.\nB: Am Anfang oder Ende des Monats?",exampleSrc:"A: The monthly costs are 500 euros.\nB: Is it debited monthly?\nA: Yes, the debit occurs monthly.\nB: At the beginning or end of the month?",funFact:"The pattern: Tag/taeglich, Woche/woechentlich, Monat/monatlich, Jahr/jaehrlich. German loves regular time adjectives. Monatlich is the rhythm of rent, insurance, and subscriptions."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius sagt: 'Ich muss eine Entscheidung treffen.' Warum treffen und nicht machen?",opts:["machen ist grammatisch falsch","treffen hat eine andere Bedeutung","treffen ist das feste Verb fuer Entscheidung im formellen Deutsch","beide sind gleich korrekt"],ans:"treffen ist das feste Verb fuer Entscheidung im formellen Deutsch",hint:"Fixed noun-verb collocations have fixed verb partners. 'Entscheidung' always pairs with 'treffen.'"},
{type:"fb",s:"Alle Optionen muessen in {1} gezogen werden.",a:["Betracht"],opts:["Betracht","Kauf","Verfuegung","Einfluss"],hint:"The fixed expression for 'to take into consideration.' You take options into your...",sSrc:"All options must be taken into consideration."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Da die Sozialleistungen zur Verfuegung stehen, muss jeder selbst eine Entscheidung treffen.' Wie viele NVV enthaelt dieser Satz?",opts:["zwei (zur Verfuegung stehen, eine Entscheidung treffen)","eine","drei","keine"],ans:"zwei (zur Verfuegung stehen, eine Entscheidung treffen)",hint:"Count the fixed noun-verb pairs. Both availability and decision-making are formal collocations."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Bis Maerz wird er die Investition in {1} {2} haben.",blanks:{"1":"Betracht","2":"gezogen"},pool:["Betracht","gezogen","Kauf","genommen","Verfuegung","gestanden"],hint:"Futur II of 'in Betracht ziehen.' By March he will have considered the investment.",sSrc:"By March he will have taken the investment into consideration."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"eine Entscheidung treffen",src:"to make a decision"},{trg:"in Betracht ziehen",src:"to consider"},{trg:"zur Verfuegung stehen",src:"to be available"},{trg:"in Kauf nehmen",src:"to accept (a drawback)"}]},

{type:"story",speaker:"mia",mood:"resolute",art:"de-ber-park-sunset",trg:"Ich werde das Elterngeld in Anspruch nehmen. Und Lukas wird seine Musikschule finanzieren. Wir nehmen die Veraenderungen in Kauf. So funktioniert das hier.",src:"I will claim the parental benefit. And Lukas will finance his music school. We accept the changes. That is how it works here."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thoughtful",art:"de-ber-park-walking",trg:"In Betracht ziehen, zur Verfuegung stehen, in Kauf nehmen. Das sind keine Woerter. Das sind Werkzeuge. Ohne sie kommt man in Deutschland nicht weiter.",src:"Consider, be available, accept the drawbacks. These are not words. They are tools. Without them, you cannot get by in Germany."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l6",title:"Bilanz ziehen",icon:"\uD83C\uDFB5",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Bilanz ziehen",desc:"Lukas proudly shows his sound workshop. Verumius reflects on the German economic system in the evening. All three grammar constructions are practiced in complex combinations.",goals:["Practice all three grammar constructions in combination","Master advanced business vocabulary","Use noun-verb combinations naturally"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-kreuzberg-studio",trg:"Kreuzberg, ein kleines Hinterhof-Studio. Ein handgemaltes Schild: 'Klangwerkstatt Kreuzberg.' Drinnen: zwei Gitarren, ein Keyboard, Kinderzeichnungen an der Wand. Lukas steht in der Mitte und grinst. Das ist sein Traum.",src:"Kreuzberg, a small backyard studio. A hand-painted sign: 'Klangwerkstatt Kreuzberg.' Inside: two guitars, a keyboard, children's drawings on the wall. Lukas stands in the middle, grinning. This is his dream."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"passionate",art:"de-ber-lukas-music-school",trg:"Ich habe eine Entscheidung getroffen. Die Musikschule ist mein Ding. Da ich Kinder unterrichte, muss ich auch Buchfuehrung machen. Stell dir vor!",src:"I made a decision. The music school is my thing. Since I teach children, I also have to do bookkeeping. Imagine that!"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"proud",art:"de-ber-verumius-proud",trg:"Du hast einen Traum verwirklicht. Bis naechstes Jahr wirst du dich etabliert haben.",src:"You realized a dream. By next year you will have established yourself."},
{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"determined",art:"de-ber-lukas-determined",trg:"Ich muss noch Eigenkapital aufbauen. Aber zumal die Nachfrage gross ist, wird es klappen.",src:"I still need to build up equity. But especially since demand is high, it will work out."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Buchfuehrung",src:"bookkeeping",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Buch + Fuehrung (leading).\n'Die Buchfuehrung muss korrekt sein.'",example:"A: Machst du die Buchfuehrung selbst?\nB: Ja, die Buchfuehrung uebernehme ich.\nA: Buchfuehrung ist Pflicht fuer jedes Unternehmen.\nB: Deshalb habe ich eine Software gekauft.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you do the bookkeeping yourself?\nB: Yes, I handle the bookkeeping.\nA: Bookkeeping is mandatory for every company.\nB: That is why I bought software.",funFact:"Every German business must keep Buecher (books). The Finanzamt can demand to see them at any time. Germans helped develop double-entry bookkeeping alongside the Italians."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Eigenkapital",src:"equity, own capital",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Eigen + Kapital.\n'Das Eigenkapital der Firma betraegt 100.000 Euro.'",example:"A: Wie hoch ist dein Eigenkapital?\nB: Bisher etwa 30.000 Euro.\nA: Das ist ein guter Anfang.\nB: Eigenkapital aufzubauen braucht Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: How high is your equity?\nB: About 30,000 euros so far.\nA: That is a good start.\nB: Building up equity takes time.",funFact:"The money you own free and clear. Contrast with Fremdkapital (borrowed money). A healthy company needs both. The ratio determines whether a bank will give you a Kredit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Fremdkapital",src:"borrowed capital, debt",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Fremd + Kapital.\n'Das Unternehmen hat zu viel Fremdkapital.'",example:"A: Wie viel Fremdkapital hat die Firma?\nB: 200.000 Euro von der Bank.\nA: Das Verhaeltnis von Eigen- zu Fremdkapital ist wichtig.\nB: Ja, zu viel Fremdkapital ist riskant.",exampleSrc:"A: How much borrowed capital does the company have?\nB: 200,000 euros from the bank.\nA: The ratio of equity to borrowed capital is important.\nB: Yes, too much borrowed capital is risky.",funFact:"Money from outside: bank loans, bonds, credit. The ratio of Eigenkapital to Fremdkapital determines a company's financial health. German banks look at this ratio before every Kredit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Gesamtkosten",src:"total costs",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine, always plural. Gesamt + Kosten.\n'Die Gesamtkosten uebersteigen das Budget.'",example:"A: Wie hoch sind die Gesamtkosten des Projekts?\nB: Die Gesamtkosten liegen bei 500.000 Euro.\nA: Das uebersteigt unser Budget.\nB: Dann muessen wir die Gesamtkosten senken.",exampleSrc:"A: How high are the total costs of the project?\nB: The total costs are 500,000 euros.\nA: That exceeds our budget.\nB: Then we need to lower the total costs.",funFact:"Always plural. 'Die Gesamtkosten uebersteigen das Budget' is every project manager's nightmare. Breaking Gesamtkosten into Einzelkosten (individual costs) is the first step to understanding where money goes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Geschaeftsbericht",src:"annual report",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Geschaeft + Bericht.\n'Den Geschaeftsbericht lesen.'",example:"A: Hast du den Geschaeftsbericht gelesen?\nB: Ja, er zeigt steigende Umsaetze.\nA: Der Geschaeftsbericht ist oeffentlich zugaenglich.\nB: Jedes boersennotierte Unternehmen muss einen veroeffentlichen.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you read the annual report?\nB: Yes, it shows rising revenues.\nA: The annual report is publicly accessible.\nB: Every listed company must publish one.",funFact:"Every listed company in Germany must publish one. It contains Bilanz, Gewinn- und Verlustrechnung, and an outlook. Investors read Geschaeftsberichte like detectives looking for clues."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Kostenstelle",src:"cost center",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Kosten + Stelle.\n'Buchen Sie das auf Kostenstelle 4711.'",example:"A: Auf welche Kostenstelle geht das?\nB: Kostenstelle 301, Marketing.\nA: Jede Abteilung hat eine eigene Kostenstelle.\nB: So kann man die Ausgaben genau zuordnen.",exampleSrc:"A: Which cost center does that go to?\nB: Cost center 301, Marketing.\nA: Every department has its own cost center.\nB: That way you can assign expenses precisely.",funFact:"A department or unit where costs are tracked. German accounting precision at its finest. The number 4711 is famous as both a cologne brand and a classic example Kostenstelle number."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Ruecklage",src:"reserve, savings set aside",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Rueck + Lage.\n'Finanzielle Ruecklagen bilden.'",example:"A: Hast du Ruecklagen fuer Notfaelle?\nB: Ja, drei Monatsgehaelter als Ruecklage.\nA: Das ist klug. Ruecklagen sind wichtig.\nB: Ohne Ruecklagen kann eine Krise fatal sein.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have reserves for emergencies?\nB: Yes, three months' salary as a reserve.\nA: That is wise. Reserves are important.\nB: Without reserves, a crisis can be fatal.",funFact:"Money laid back for emergencies. The German savings mentality in one word. Financial advisors recommend three to six Monatsgehaelter as Ruecklage. Better safe than insolvent."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Zahlungsbilanz",src:"balance of payments",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Zahlung + Bilanz.\n'Die Zahlungsbilanz eines Landes.'",example:"A: Die Zahlungsbilanz zeigt alle internationalen Transaktionen.\nB: Ist sie positiv oder negativ?\nA: Deutschlands Zahlungsbilanz ist positiv.\nB: Das heisst, mehr Geld fliesst rein als raus.",exampleSrc:"A: The balance of payments shows all international transactions.\nB: Is it positive or negative?\nA: Germany's balance of payments is positive.\nB: That means more money flows in than out.",funFact:"All financial transactions between one country and the rest of the world. Broader than Handelsbilanz: includes services, investments, and transfers. Germany's has been positive for decades."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Monopol",src:"monopoly",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Greek monos + polein.\n'Ein Monopol auf etwas haben.'",example:"A: Hat die Deutsche Bahn ein Monopol?\nB: Praktisch ja, ein Quasi-Monopol.\nA: Das Kartellamt kaempft gegen Monopole.\nB: Wettbewerb ist besser fuer die Verbraucher.",exampleSrc:"A: Does Deutsche Bahn have a monopoly?\nB: Practically yes, a quasi-monopoly.\nA: The cartel office fights against monopolies.\nB: Competition is better for consumers.",funFact:"Germany's Kartellamt (cartel office) fights Monopole. Deutsche Bahn is often called a Quasi-Monopol on rail. Same word internationally from the Greek for 'alone selling.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"Fonds",src:"fund (investment)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From French fonds.\nPronounced 'fo' (silent -nds).",example:"A: In welchen Fonds investierst du?\nB: In einen ETF-Fonds.\nA: Fonds sind beliebter als Einzelaktien.\nB: Ja, sie streuen das Risiko besser.",exampleSrc:"A: Which fund do you invest in?\nB: In an ETF fund.\nA: Funds are more popular than individual stocks.\nB: Yes, they spread the risk better.",funFact:"Pronounced 'fo' with a silent -nds (French style). Germany's most popular investment form: ETF-Fonds. The French banking term entered German and kept its French pronunciation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"solvent",src:"solvent, able to pay debts",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"From Latin solvere (to pay).\n'Das Unternehmen ist solvent.'",example:"A: Ist die Firma noch solvent?\nB: Ja, die Firma ist solvent.\nA: Solvente Unternehmen finden leichter Kredite.\nB: Im Gegensatz zu insolventen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the company still solvent?\nB: Yes, the company is solvent.\nA: Solvent companies find loans more easily.\nB: In contrast to insolvent ones.",funFact:"The opposite of insolvent. When a company can pay its debts, it is solvent. The adjective that banks want to hear before giving a Kredit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"branchenspezifisch",src:"industry-specific",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Branche + spezifisch. 19 letters.\n'Branchenspezifische Regelungen.'",example:"A: Es gibt branchenspezifische Vorschriften.\nB: Fuer welche Branchen?\nA: Jede Branche hat branchenspezifische Regeln.\nB: Die Musikbranche auch?",exampleSrc:"A: There are industry-specific regulations.\nB: For which industries?\nA: Every industry has industry-specific rules.\nB: The music industry too?",funFact:"At 19 letters, a typical B2 compound adjective. Every sector has its own branchenspezifische Regelungen. German bureaucracy customizes rules per Branche."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Anspruch nehmen",src:"to make use of, to claim",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Anspruch + nehmen.\n'Elterngeld in Anspruch nehmen.'",example:"A: Moechten Sie Elterngeld in Anspruch nehmen?\nB: Ja, ich nehme es in Anspruch.\nA: Das ist Ihr gutes Recht.\nB: Wie lange kann man es in Anspruch nehmen?",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like to claim parental benefit?\nB: Yes, I am claiming it.\nA: That is your good right.\nB: How long can you claim it?",funFact:"You take a claim. Formal, bureaucratic, but essential for accessing German benefits. 'Elterngeld in Anspruch nehmen' is the key phrase for new parents navigating the system."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Bezug nehmen auf",src:"to refer to",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Bezug + nehmen + auf.\n'Ich nehme Bezug auf Ihr Schreiben.'",example:"A: Ich nehme Bezug auf unser Gespraech.\nB: Welches Gespraech meinen Sie?\nA: Bezug nehmend auf die letzte Sitzung...\nB: Ah, die Sitzung vom letzten Dienstag.",exampleSrc:"A: I refer to our conversation.\nB: Which conversation do you mean?\nA: Referring to the last meeting...\nB: Ah, the meeting from last Tuesday.",funFact:"Standard opening in formal correspondence. 'Ich nehme Bezug auf Ihr Schreiben vom 5. Mai' connects your letter to theirs. The cross-reference formula of German business writing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zur Kenntnis nehmen",src:"to take note of, to acknowledge",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Kenntnis + nehmen.\n'Ich nehme das zur Kenntnis.'",example:"A: Wir nehmen Ihre Beschwerde zur Kenntnis.\nB: Und was passiert dann?\nA: Nehmen Sie bitte zur Kenntnis, dass die Frist ablaeuft.\nB: Zur Kenntnis genommen.",exampleSrc:"A: We take note of your complaint.\nB: And what happens then?\nA: Please take note that the deadline is expiring.\nB: Noted.",funFact:"You take something into your knowledge. Can be neutral or cold: 'Ich nehme das zur Kenntnis' sometimes means 'I acknowledge that, but I do not agree.' Tone reveals everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Frage stellen",src:"to call into question, to challenge",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Frage + stellen.\n'Die Ergebnisse in Frage stellen.'",example:"A: Darf man die Ergebnisse in Frage stellen?\nB: Natuerlich. Alles darf man in Frage stellen.\nA: Er stellt die ganze Strategie in Frage.\nB: Das ist sein Recht.",exampleSrc:"A: May one call the results into question?\nB: Of course. Everything may be questioned.\nA: He is questioning the entire strategy.\nB: That is his right.",funFact:"You place something into the realm of questions. Intellectual, critical, essential for B2-level discourse. Not aggressive, but assertive: demanding evidence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"fusionieren",src:"to merge, to fuse",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Zwei Konzerne fusionieren.'",example:"A: Die zwei Konzerne werden fusionieren.\nB: Wann findet die Fusion statt?\nA: Sie fusionieren zum 1. Januar.\nB: Das wird den Markt veraendern.",exampleSrc:"A: The two corporations will merge.\nB: When does the merger take place?\nA: They merge on January 1.\nB: That will change the market.",funFact:"From Latin fusio (melting). When companies melt into one. Germany's Kartellamt must approve every major Fusion to prevent Monopole from forming."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bilanzieren",src:"to draw up a balance sheet, to take stock",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Am Jahresende bilanzieren wir.'",example:"A: Am Jahresende muessen wir bilanzieren.\nB: Was zeigt die Bilanz?\nA: Wir haben positiv bilanziert.\nB: Gewinn oder Verlust? Positiv klingt gut.",exampleSrc:"A: At year's end we must draw up the balance.\nB: What does the balance show?\nA: We have a positive balance.\nB: Profit or loss? Positive sounds good.",funFact:"Both literal (accounting) and figurative (life reflection). 'Am Jahresende Bilanz ziehen' means both crunching numbers and reflecting on what was achieved."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Da Lukas Eigenkapital braucht, wird er bis naechstes Jahr Ruecklagen gebildet haben, zumal die Nachfrage gross ist.' Welche Konstruktionen sind enthalten?",opts:["Nur Kausalsaetze","Praeteritum + Futur II","Kausalsatz mit da + Futur II + Kausalsatz mit zumal","Nur Futur II"],ans:"Kausalsatz mit da + Futur II + Kausalsatz mit zumal",hint:"Three constructions in one sentence: da-clause (cause), Futur II (completed future), zumal-clause (emphasized cause)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Firma stellt die Ergebnisse in {1}.",a:["Frage"],opts:["Frage","Betracht","Kauf","Kenntnis"],hint:"To doubt or question something. The fixed noun partner means 'question.'",sSrc:"The company calls the results into question."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Bezug nehmend auf Ihren Brief moechte ich Stellung nehmen, da die Zahlen in Frage gestellt wurden.' Wie viele NVV sind enthalten?",opts:["zwei","eine","vier","drei (Bezug nehmen auf, Stellung nehmen, in Frage stellen)"],ans:"drei (Bezug nehmen auf, Stellung nehmen, in Frage stellen)",hint:"Count the fixed noun-verb pairs. Referencing, taking a position, and questioning are all formal collocations."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Bis Ende des Jahres wird er die Bilanz {1} haben, {2} das Geschaeftsjahr zu Ende geht.",blanks:{"1":"gezogen","2":"da"},pool:["gezogen","da","ziehen","zumal","gemacht","weil"],hint:"Futur II of 'Bilanz ziehen' (to take stock) plus a formal causal connector.",sSrc:"By the end of the year he will have taken stock, since the fiscal year is ending."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"in Anspruch nehmen",src:"to make use of"},{trg:"Bezug nehmen auf",src:"to refer to"},{trg:"zur Kenntnis nehmen",src:"to acknowledge"},{trg:"in Frage stellen",src:"to question"}]},

{type:"story",speaker:"lukas",mood:"content",art:"de-ber-kreuzberg-evening",trg:"Weisst du, Verumius, Buchfuehrung ist nicht so schlimm. Man muss nur jeden Beleg zur Kenntnis nehmen. Und genug Ruecklagen bilden. Dann laeuft der Laden.",src:"You know, Verumius, bookkeeping is not so bad. You just have to take note of every receipt. And build enough reserves. Then the shop runs."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-verumius-laughing",trg:"Lukas, der Musiker, erklaert mir Buchfuehrung. Berlin veraendert jeden.",src:"Lukas, the musician, is explaining bookkeeping to me. Berlin changes everyone."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l7",title:"Zahlen, Daten, Fakten",icon:"\uD83D\uDCCA",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Zahlen, Daten, Fakten",desc:"Hard quiz mode. Prove your mastery of financial German. Test all three grammar constructions. Show you can build complex economic arguments.",goals:["Prove mastery of financial German","Test all three grammar constructions","Show ability to build complex economic arguments"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"focused",art:"de-ber-library-study",trg:"Staatsbibliothek, Potsdamer Platz. Verumius sitzt zwischen Wirtschaftslehrbüchern und Zeitungsartikeln. Heute wird geprüft, was er gelernt hat. Zahlen, Daten, Fakten. Kein Raten mehr.",src:"State library, Potsdamer Platz. Verumius sits among economics textbooks and newspaper articles. Today he will test what he has learned. Numbers, data, facts. No more guessing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Arbeitgeber",src:"employer",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Arbeit + Geber.\nDer Arbeitgeber gibt Arbeit.",example:"A: Wer ist dein Arbeitgeber?\nB: Mein Arbeitgeber ist ein Konzern in Frankfurt.\nA: Arbeitgeber haben viele Pflichten.\nB: Ja, Sozialversicherung, Urlaub, Kuendigungsschutz.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is your employer?\nB: My employer is a corporation in Frankfurt.\nA: Employers have many obligations.\nB: Yes, social insurance, vacation, dismissal protection.",funFact:"The one who gives work. In German law, Arbeitgeber have extensive obligations: social insurance, vacation days, sick pay. The 'giver' gives much more than just work."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Arbeitnehmer",src:"employee",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Arbeit + Nehmer.\nDer Arbeitnehmer nimmt die Arbeit an.",example:"A: Wie viele Arbeitnehmer hat die Firma?\nB: Ueber 500 Arbeitnehmer.\nA: Das Arbeitnehmerrecht ist stark in Deutschland.\nB: Ja, Kuendigungsschutz ist umfassend.",exampleSrc:"A: How many employees does the company have?\nB: Over 500 employees.\nA: Employee rights are strong in Germany.\nB: Yes, dismissal protection is comprehensive.",funFact:"The one who takes work. The pair Arbeitgeber/Arbeitnehmer is perfectly symmetrical: one gives, one takes. German labor law strongly protects the Nehmer."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Angebot",src:"supply, offer",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. An + Gebot (bid).\n'Angebot und Nachfrage' (supply and demand).",example:"A: Das Angebot uebersteigt die Nachfrage.\nB: Dann sinken die Preise.\nA: Wir machen Ihnen ein Angebot.\nB: Ich werde das Angebot prufen.",exampleSrc:"A: Supply exceeds demand.\nB: Then prices fall.\nA: We are making you an offer.\nB: I will review the offer.",funFact:"The counterpart to Nachfrage in every economics textbook. 'Angebot und Nachfrage' is lesson one. Also: 'ein Angebot machen' (to make an offer). One word, two key meanings."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Krise",src:"crisis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Greek krisis (decision).\n'Eine Wirtschaftskrise' (economic crisis).",example:"A: Die Finanzkrise hat viele Unternehmen getroffen.\nB: Wie hat Deutschland die Krise ueberstanden?\nA: Mit Konjunkturpaketen und Kurzarbeit.\nB: Jede Krise ist auch eine Chance.",exampleSrc:"A: The financial crisis hit many companies.\nB: How did Germany survive the crisis?\nA: With stimulus packages and short-time work.\nB: Every crisis is also an opportunity.",funFact:"The Greek root means the moment of decision, not the disaster itself. 'Wirtschaftskrise' (economic crisis), 'Finanzkrise' (financial crisis). In German, the Krise is where you must choose."},
{type:"teach",trg:"unter Beweis stellen",src:"to prove, to demonstrate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Beweis + stellen.\n'Seine Kompetenz unter Beweis stellen.'",example:"A: Er hat seine Faehigkeiten unter Beweis gestellt.\nB: Wie hat er das getan?\nA: Durch hervorragende Ergebnisse.\nB: Kompetenz muss man unter Beweis stellen, nicht nur behaupten.",exampleSrc:"A: He demonstrated his abilities.\nB: How did he do that?\nA: Through excellent results.\nB: Competence must be proven, not just claimed.",funFact:"You place something under proof. More formal than beweisen. In business, you 'stellen Ihre Kompetenz unter Beweis' through results, not words."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Kraft treten",src:"to come into force/effect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Kraft + treten.\n'Das Gesetz tritt am 1. Januar in Kraft.'",example:"A: Wann tritt das Gesetz in Kraft?\nB: Es tritt am 1. Juli in Kraft.\nA: Ab dann gelten die neuen Regeln.\nB: Bis zum Inkrafttreten haben wir noch Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: When does the law come into force?\nB: It comes into force on July 1.\nA: From then on, the new rules apply.\nB: We still have time until it takes effect.",funFact:"A law steps into force. Legal German at its most precise. 'Inkrafttreten' (the coming into force) is the noun form. Every German law has an exact date of Inkrafttreten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Massnahmen ergreifen",src:"to take measures",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Massnahmen + ergreifen.\n'Die Regierung muss Massnahmen ergreifen.'",example:"A: Welche Massnahmen hat die Regierung ergriffen?\nB: Steuererleichterungen und Subventionen.\nA: Reichen diese Massnahmen aus?\nB: Wir muessen weitere Massnahmen ergreifen.",exampleSrc:"A: What measures did the government take?\nB: Tax relief and subsidies.\nA: Are these measures sufficient?\nB: We need to take further measures.",funFact:"You seize the measures. Politicians' favorite phrase during any Krise. 'Sofortmassnahmen ergreifen' (to take immediate measures) signals urgency and action."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Bilanz ziehen",src:"to take stock, to sum up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Bilanz + ziehen.\n'Am Jahresende Bilanz ziehen.'",example:"A: Lass uns Bilanz ziehen.\nB: Ja, es ist Zeit, Bilanz zu ziehen.\nA: Die Bilanz faellt positiv aus.\nB: Gut. Naechstes Jahr ziehen wir wieder Bilanz.",exampleSrc:"A: Let us take stock.\nB: Yes, it is time to take stock.\nA: The assessment is positive.\nB: Good. Next year we will take stock again.",funFact:"You draw a balance line. Both financial (accounting) and philosophical (life reflection). Every year, companies and individuals 'ziehen Bilanz' over what was achieved."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Konkurs anmelden",src:"to file for bankruptcy",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable. Konkurs + anmelden.\n'Die Firma hat Konkurs angemeldet.'",example:"A: Hat die Firma Konkurs angemeldet?\nB: Ja, sie hat letzte Woche Konkurs angemeldet.\nA: Wie viele Arbeitnehmer sind betroffen?\nB: Ueber 200 verlieren ihre Stelle.",exampleSrc:"A: Did the company file for bankruptcy?\nB: Yes, it filed for bankruptcy last week.\nA: How many employees are affected?\nB: Over 200 will lose their positions.",funFact:"You register your inability to pay. The formal legal step when a business fails. Separable: 'Er meldet Konkurs an.' The German Insolvenzrecht gives debtors a second chance after six years."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Verantwortung uebernehmen",src:"to take responsibility",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Verantwortung + uebernehmen.\n'Jeder muss Verantwortung uebernehmen.'",example:"A: Wer uebernimmt die Verantwortung?\nB: Der Geschaeftsfuehrer uebernimmt die Verantwortung.\nA: Verantwortung zu uebernehmen ist mutig.\nB: Ja, aber notwendig.",exampleSrc:"A: Who takes responsibility?\nB: The managing director takes responsibility.\nA: Taking responsibility is courageous.\nB: Yes, but necessary.",funFact:"You take responsibility over onto yourself. Germany's civic motto. In politics and business, 'Verantwortung uebernehmen' is the difference between a leader and a figurehead."},
{type:"teach",trg:"eine Rolle spielen",src:"to play a role, to matter",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Rolle + spielen.\n'Geld spielt eine grosse Rolle.'",example:"A: Spielt der Preis eine Rolle?\nB: Ja, der Preis spielt eine entscheidende Rolle.\nA: Und die Qualitaet?\nB: Beide spielen eine wichtige Rolle.",exampleSrc:"A: Does price play a role?\nB: Yes, price plays a decisive role.\nA: And quality?\nB: Both play an important role.",funFact:"Same metaphor as English: life is theater. Every factor plays its part. 'Eine grosse Rolle spielen' (to play a major role) and 'keine Rolle spielen' (to not matter) are everyday expressions."},
{type:"teach",trg:"Rechnung tragen",src:"to take into account, to bear in mind",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Rechnung + tragen.\n'Den Risiken Rechnung tragen.'",example:"A: Wir muessen den Risiken Rechnung tragen.\nB: Wie tragen wir dem Rechnung?\nA: Durch bessere Planung.\nB: Dem veraenderten Markt muss man Rechnung tragen.",exampleSrc:"A: We must take the risks into account.\nB: How do we account for that?\nA: Through better planning.\nB: One must take the changed market into account.",funFact:"You carry the account. Formal, used in reports and speeches. Takes dative: 'den Risiken Rechnung tragen.' The expression of due diligence in German business."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verstaatlichen",src:"to nationalize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable. Ver- + Staat + -lichen.\nOpposite of privatisieren.",example:"A: Soll man die Energieversorgung verstaatlichen?\nB: Das ist eine politische Frage.\nA: Einige Laender haben ihre Banken verstaatlicht.\nB: In der Krise verstaatlicht der Staat, danach privatisiert er.",exampleSrc:"A: Should energy supply be nationalized?\nB: That is a political question.\nA: Some countries nationalized their banks.\nB: In a crisis the state nationalizes, afterwards it privatizes.",funFact:"The opposite of privatisieren. Germany has nationalized and privatized in cycles. During the 2008 financial crisis, several European countries temporarily verstaatlichten banks."},
{type:"teach",trg:"amortisieren",src:"to amortize, to recoup",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb. Reflexive: sich amortisieren.\n'Die Investition amortisiert sich in drei Jahren.'",example:"A: Wann amortisiert sich die Investition?\nB: In etwa drei Jahren.\nA: Das ist ein akzeptabler Zeitraum.\nB: Ja, danach macht sie Gewinn.",exampleSrc:"A: When does the investment pay for itself?\nB: In about three years.\nA: That is an acceptable timeframe.\nB: Yes, after that it generates profit.",funFact:"From French 'amortir' (to extinguish/pay off). Reflexive when meaning 'to pay off': 'Die Investition amortisiert sich.' The moment of Amortisation is when costs equal returns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"liquidieren",src:"to liquidate, to wind up",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Ein Unternehmen liquidieren.'",example:"A: Die Firma wird liquidiert.\nB: Was passiert mit den Vermoegenswerten?\nA: Alles wird verkauft und verteilt.\nB: Liquidieren ist das Ende einer Firma.",exampleSrc:"A: The company is being liquidated.\nB: What happens to the assets?\nA: Everything is sold and distributed.\nB: Liquidating is the end of a company.",funFact:"Making the accounts liquid: turning everything into cash. From Latin 'liquidare' (to make clear/settle). In business: winding up a company. The final step after insolvency."},
{type:"teach",trg:"outsourcen",src:"to outsource",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From English. Pronounced with English phonetics.\n'Dienstleistungen outsourcen.'",example:"A: Sollen wir die IT outsourcen?\nB: Das spart Kosten.\nA: Viele Firmen outsourcen ihre Buchhaltung.\nB: Der deutsche Ausdruck waere 'auslagern.'",exampleSrc:"A: Should we outsource the IT?\nB: That saves costs.\nA: Many companies outsource their accounting.\nB: The German expression would be 'auslagern.'",funFact:"German borrowed it wholesale from English. Pronounced with English phonetics. Some purists prefer 'auslagern' but outsourcen dominates business jargon. A Denglisch classic."},
{type:"teach",trg:"budgetieren",src:"to budget",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Kosten budgetieren' (to budget costs).",example:"A: Haben Sie die Kosten budgetiert?\nB: Ja, alles ist budgetiert.\nA: Gut budgetieren ist die halbe Miete.\nB: Ohne Budget kein Ueberblick.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you budgeted the costs?\nB: Yes, everything is budgeted.\nA: Good budgeting is half the battle.\nB: Without a budget, no overview.",funFact:"The French word 'budget' came from Old French 'bougette' (small bag). Planning what fits in your financial bag. The -ieren ending makes it a standard German business verb."},
{type:"teach",trg:"quartalweise",src:"quarterly",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Quartal + -weise. Every three months.\n'Quartalweise Berichte.'",example:"A: Der Bericht erscheint quartalweise.\nB: Also viermal im Jahr?\nA: Genau. Q1, Q2, Q3, Q4.\nB: Die quartalweisen Zahlen sind wichtig fuer Anleger.",exampleSrc:"A: The report is published quarterly.\nB: So four times a year?\nA: Exactly. Q1, Q2, Q3, Q4.\nB: The quarterly figures are important for investors.",funFact:"German business runs on quarterly cycles. Quartalszahlen (quarterly figures) move stock prices. The -weise suffix creates manner adverbs: monatlich/monatweise, quartalweise, stueckweise."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Da die Regierung Massnahmen ergriffen hat, wird die Krise ueberwunden sein.' Welche Konstruktionen sind kombiniert?",opts:["Kausalsatz mit da + NVV + Futur II","Nur Futur II","Kausalsatz + Futur II","NVV allein"],ans:"Kausalsatz mit da + NVV + Futur II",hint:"Three constructions: da-clause, 'Massnahmen ergreifen' (NVV), and Futur II (completed future)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das neue Gesetz tritt am 1. Januar in {1}.",a:["Kraft"],opts:["Kraft","Frage","Kauf","Betracht"],hint:"The fixed expression for a law coming into effect. It enters into...",sSrc:"The new law comes into force on January 1."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Er wird wohl schon Konkurs angemeldet haben.' Dieses Futur II drueckt aus...",opts:["einen definitiven Zukunftsplan","einen Befehl","einen Wunsch","eine Annahme ueber etwas, das wahrscheinlich bereits geschehen ist"],ans:"eine Annahme ueber etwas, das wahrscheinlich bereits geschehen ist",hint:"Futur II with 'wohl' expresses a probability judgment about a completed action."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} er Verantwortung uebernommen hat, wird die Firma sich bis 2026 {2} haben.",blanks:{"1":"Da","2":"erholt"},pool:["Da","erholt","Weil","erholen","Zumal","amortisiert"],hint:"Formal causal clause + Futur II. 'Since he took responsibility, the firm will have recovered.'",sSrc:"Since he took responsibility, the firm will have recovered by 2026."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Insofern als die Nachfrage steigt, spielen neue Maerkte eine grosse Rolle.' Was bedeutet 'insofern als' hier?",opts:["weil","obwohl","trotz","insoweit wie / in dem Masse, in dem"],ans:"insoweit wie / in dem Masse, in dem",hint:"A precise, academic causal connector. It limits the scope of the statement."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Investition wird sich in drei Jahren {1}.",a:["amortisieren"],opts:["amortisieren","liquidieren","budgetieren","privatisieren"],hint:"When an investment pays for itself. The reflexive form: sich amortisieren.",sSrc:"The investment will pay for itself in three years."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Massnahmen ergreifen",src:"to take measures"},{trg:"Bilanz ziehen",src:"to take stock"},{trg:"Verantwortung uebernehmen",src:"to take responsibility"},{trg:"eine Rolle spielen",src:"to play a role"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"In einem Geschaeftsbericht steht: 'Wir muessen den veraenderten Bedingungen Rechnung ___.' Welches Verb vervollstaendigt die NVV?",opts:["tragen","stellen","nehmen","ziehen"],ans:"tragen",hint:"'Rechnung tragen' means 'to take into account.' You carry the account of something."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"confident",art:"de-ber-library-leaving",trg:"Zahlen, Daten, Fakten. Ich habe unter Beweis gestellt, dass ich die Wirtschaftssprache beherrsche. Zumindest auf dem Papier. Morgen kommt die Praxis.",src:"Numbers, data, facts. I have proven that I command the language of economics. At least on paper. Tomorrow comes the practice."}
]},
{id:"deu_r31l8",title:"Das System verstehen",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Das System verstehen",desc:"Verumius sits at his desk in the evening and draws a mind map of the German economic system. All NVV, causal connectors, and Futur II in complex arguments. The system finally makes sense.",goals:["Synthesize everything from Unit 31","Use all NVV, causal connectors, and Futur II in complex arguments","Understand the German economic model"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-ber-apartment-mindmap",trg:"Verumius' Wohnung, abends. Er sitzt am Schreibtisch und zeichnet eine Mindmap. Steuern, Rente, Krankenversicherung, Kindergeld, Elterngeld: alles durch Pfeile verbunden. Das System ergibt jetzt Sinn.",src:"Verumius's apartment, evening. He sits at his desk, drawing a mind-map. Taxes, pension, health insurance, child benefit, parental benefit: all connected by arrows. The system makes sense now."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"reflective",art:"de-ber-verumius-desk",trg:"Ich habe Bilanz gezogen. Da ich das Steuersystem verstehe und die Sozialleistungen in Anspruch nehmen kann, fuehle ich mich in Deutschland angekommen.",src:"I have taken stock. Since I understand the tax system and can make use of the social benefits, I feel I have arrived in Germany."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"concluding",art:"de-ber-apartment-corkboard",trg:"Er pinnt die Mindmap neben sein Korkbrett mit den Dokumenten des deutschen Lebens. Die Sammlung waechst: Anmeldung, Mietvertrag, Lauftreff-Mitgliedskarte, Arbeitsvertrag. Und jetzt: ein Verstaendnis des Systems.",src:"He pins the mind-map next to his corkboard of German life documents. The collection grows: registration, rental contract, running club membership, work contract. And now: an understanding of the system."},

{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"peaceful",art:"de-ber-apartment-window-night",trg:"Soziale Marktwirtschaft. Man zahlt viel, aber man bekommt auch viel zurueck. Da ich das jetzt verstehe, kann ich endlich mitreden. Nicht nur leben in Deutschland, sondern verstehen, wie es funktioniert.",src:"Social market economy. You pay a lot, but you get a lot back too. Since I understand that now, I can finally join the conversation. Not just living in Germany, but understanding how it works."},

{type:"teach",trg:"zum Ausdruck bringen",src:"to express",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Ausdruck + bringen.\n'Seine Meinung zum Ausdruck bringen.'",example:"A: Wie bringt man seine Meinung zum Ausdruck?\nB: In einer formellen Stellungnahme.\nA: Er brachte seine Bedenken zum Ausdruck.\nB: Das war mutig und wichtig.",exampleSrc:"A: How does one express one's opinion?\nB: In a formal statement.\nA: He expressed his concerns.\nB: That was courageous and important.",funFact:"You bring something to expression. More formal than 'ausdruecken.' Used in speeches and formal writing. The NVV of diplomatic and official communication."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Erwaegung ziehen",src:"to consider, to contemplate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Fixed NVV. Erwaegung + ziehen.\nMore careful than 'in Betracht ziehen.'",example:"A: Wir ziehen einen Standortwechsel in Erwaegung.\nB: Aus welchem Grund?\nA: Da die Mietkosten steigen.\nB: Das sollte man gruendlich in Erwaegung ziehen.",exampleSrc:"A: We are considering a change of location.\nB: For what reason?\nA: Since rental costs are rising.\nB: That should be carefully considered.",funFact:"More thoughtful than 'in Betracht ziehen.' You pull something into deliberation. 'Wir ziehen einen Wechsel in Erwaegung' implies careful, slow weighing of pros and cons."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erwirtschaften",src:"to generate (profit/revenue)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable. Er- + wirtschaften.\n'Gewinne erwirtschaften.'",example:"A: Wie viel Gewinn hat die Firma erwirtschaftet?\nB: 2 Millionen Euro.\nA: Das wurde hart erwirtschaftet.\nB: Ja, der Erfolg wurde nicht geschenkt.",exampleSrc:"A: How much profit did the company generate?\nB: 2 million euros.\nA: That was hard-earned.\nB: Yes, the success was not given as a gift.",funFact:"The er- prefix means achieving a result through effort. Managing your economy until you produce results. 'Gewinne erwirtschaften' is the formal business term for making money."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abschreiben",src:"to depreciate, to write off",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ab + schreiben.\n'Einen Verlust abschreiben.'",example:"A: Kann man die Geraete abschreiben?\nB: Ja, ueber fuenf Jahre.\nA: Wie viel schreiben wir dieses Jahr ab?\nB: 20% der Anschaffungskosten.",exampleSrc:"A: Can the equipment be depreciated?\nB: Yes, over five years.\nA: How much do we write off this year?\nB: 20% of the acquisition costs.",funFact:"Two meanings: depreciate in accounting and write off as a loss. Also means 'to copy' in school. Context decides: tax office or classroom. Separable: 'Wir schreiben 10.000 Euro ab.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"ausschuetten",src:"to distribute (dividends)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Aus + schuetten.\n'Dividenden ausschuetten.'",example:"A: Wann werden die Dividenden ausgeschuettet?\nB: Im Mai nach der Hauptversammlung.\nA: Wie viel wird ausgeschuettet?\nB: 3 Euro pro Aktie.",exampleSrc:"A: When are dividends distributed?\nB: In May after the annual meeting.\nA: How much is distributed?\nB: 3 euros per share.",funFact:"You pour profits out to the shareholders. Separable: 'Die Firma schuettet Dividenden aus.' German companies typically ausschuetten once a year, unlike quarterly in the US."},
{type:"teach",trg:"subventionieren",src:"to subsidize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Non-separable -ieren verb.\n'Die Landwirtschaft subventionieren.'",example:"A: Soll der Staat die Landwirtschaft subventionieren?\nB: Das wird seit Jahren diskutiert.\nA: Viele Branchen werden subventioniert.\nB: Die Frage ist: wie lange noch?",exampleSrc:"A: Should the state subsidize agriculture?\nB: That has been debated for years.\nA: Many sectors are subsidized.\nB: The question is: for how much longer?",funFact:"Government money flows to support sectors that would otherwise struggle. 'Subventionen abbauen' (to reduce subsidies) is a perpetual political debate in Germany and the EU."},
{type:"teach",trg:"tilgen",src:"to repay (a debt), to extinguish",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Middle High German.\n'Schulden tilgen' (to repay debts).",example:"A: Wann werden die Schulden getilgt?\nB: In zehn Jahren.\nA: Monatlich tilgen wir 500 Euro.\nB: Nach zehn Jahren ist die Schuld getilgt.",exampleSrc:"A: When will the debts be repaid?\nB: In ten years.\nA: We repay 500 euros monthly.\nB: After ten years the debt is extinguished.",funFact:"You destroy the debt by paying it off. From Middle High German 'tilgen' meaning to destroy or erase. The word carries the weight of elimination. Every final payment is an act of tilgen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"da",src:"since, as (causal conjunction)",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Formal written causal connector. Verb-final.\n'Da er investiert, waechst sein Kapital.'",example:"A: Da die Wirtschaft waechst, steigen die Einnahmen.\nB: Das klingt logisch.\nA: Da er Steuern zahlt, hat er Anspruch auf Leistungen.\nB: Ursache und Wirkung.",exampleSrc:"A: Since the economy grows, revenues rise.\nB: That sounds logical.\nA: Since he pays taxes, he is entitled to benefits.\nB: Cause and effect.",funFact:"As a causal conjunction: 'since/as.' Formal, written. Places the cause before the effect. Different from temporal 'da' (there/then). Context decides."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zumal",src:"especially since",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Adds emphasis to a reason. Stronger than da.\n'Die Investition lohnt sich, zumal die Zinsen niedrig sind.'",example:"A: Das Projekt lohnt sich, zumal wir Subventionen erhalten.\nB: Zumal die Nachfrage steigt.\nA: Investieren wir, zumal das Risiko gering ist.\nB: Einverstanden. Zumal wir Ruecklagen haben.",exampleSrc:"A: The project is worthwhile, especially since we receive subsidies.\nB: Especially since demand is rising.\nA: Let us invest, especially since the risk is low.\nB: Agreed. Especially since we have reserves.",funFact:"'Zu' + 'mal' (time/instance). Adds weight to a reason. Not just because, but especially because. Stronger than 'da,' more elegant than 'besonders weil.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"umso mehr als",src:"all the more since",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Emphasizes that a cause makes a claim even more true.\n'Das ist wichtig, umso mehr als die Konkurrenz waechst.'",example:"A: Wir muessen investieren, umso mehr als die Konkurrenz stark ist.\nB: Das stimmt, umso mehr als wir hinterherhinken.\nA: Qualitaet ist wichtig, umso mehr als der Markt waechst.\nB: Ja, umso mehr als die Kunden anspruchsvoller werden.",exampleSrc:"A: We must invest, all the more since competition is strong.\nB: That is true, all the more since we are lagging behind.\nA: Quality is important, all the more since the market is growing.\nB: Yes, all the more since customers are becoming more demanding.",funFact:"Emphasizes that the cause makes the statement even more true. Academic and journalistic register. The triple-word connector that intensifies any argument."},
{type:"teach",trg:"naemlich",src:"namely, you see (explanatory)",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Placed AFTER the verb in main clause.\n'Er investiert nicht; er hat naemlich kein Kapital.'",example:"A: Er kann nicht investieren. Er hat naemlich kein Kapital.\nB: Das ist naemlich das Problem.\nA: Wir muessen sparen. Die Kosten sind naemlich zu hoch.\nB: Naemlich seit letztem Quartal.",exampleSrc:"A: He cannot invest. He has no capital, you see.\nB: That is precisely the problem.\nA: We must save. The costs are too high, you see.\nB: Namely since last quarter.",funFact:"From 'Name' (name). Explains the reason after the fact. Placed AFTER the verb in the main clause. Conversational but also formal. 'Er hat naemlich kein Geld' provides the reason casually."},
{type:"teach",trg:"und zwar",src:"namely, specifically",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Specifies or clarifies the preceding statement.\n'Wir sparen, und zwar 20%.'",example:"A: Wir muessen Kosten senken, und zwar sofort.\nB: Und zwar um wie viel Prozent?\nA: Um 15%, und zwar in allen Abteilungen.\nB: Das ist ambitioniert.",exampleSrc:"A: We must cut costs, namely immediately.\nB: And by what percentage exactly?\nA: By 15%, namely in all departments.\nB: That is ambitious.",funFact:"Introduces the precise detail. Punchy and efficient. 'Und zwar' says: I will now tell you exactly what I mean. The clarifier of German argumentation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schliesslich",src:"after all, ultimately",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"From schliessen (to close). Provides concluding reason.\n'Er arbeitet hart; schliesslich hat er Schulden.'",example:"A: Er arbeitet hart. Schliesslich hat er Schulden.\nB: Schliesslich muss er seine Familie ernaehren.\nA: Investieren lohnt sich. Schliesslich waechst der Markt.\nB: Schliesslich ist Wachstum das Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: He works hard. After all, he has debts.\nB: After all, he has to feed his family.\nA: Investing is worthwhile. After all, the market is growing.\nB: After all, growth is the goal.",funFact:"Provides the concluding reason. 'After all' implies the listener should have known. Slightly argumentative. From 'schliessen' (to close): closing the argument."},
{type:"teach",trg:"insofern als",src:"insofar as",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Academic, precise, limiting connector.\n'Das stimmt, insofern als die Daten korrekt sind.'",example:"A: Das ist rentabel, insofern als die Nachfrage stabil bleibt.\nB: Insofern als die Daten stimmen, ja.\nA: Insofern als wir solvent bleiben, koennen wir expandieren.\nB: Eine wichtige Einschraenkung.",exampleSrc:"A: That is profitable, insofar as demand remains stable.\nB: Insofar as the data is correct, yes.\nA: Insofar as we remain solvent, we can expand.\nB: An important qualification.",funFact:"The academic, precise causal connector that limits a claim. 'This is true, but only to the extent that...' Essential for nuanced B2-level argumentation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"in Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass",src:"in view of the fact that",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Most formal causal connector. Bureaucratic.\n'In Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass die Kosten steigen...'",example:"A: In Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass die Kosten steigen, muessen wir sparen.\nB: Das klingt sehr formell.\nA: In Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass Arbeitsplaetze betroffen sind...\nB: ...muessen wir vorsichtig handeln.",exampleSrc:"A: In view of the fact that costs are rising, we must save.\nB: That sounds very formal.\nA: In view of the fact that jobs are affected...\nB: ...we must act carefully.",funFact:"Seven words to say 'because.' The most formal causal connector in German. Bureaucratic, political, and legal. Used when every other word must carry weight."},
{type:"teach",trg:"namentlich",src:"namely, specifically (formal)",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"More formal than 'und zwar.' Written register.\n'Einige Branchen, namentlich die Automobilindustrie.'",example:"A: Einige Branchen profitieren, namentlich die Techbranche.\nB: Und namentlich der Einzelhandel?\nA: Namentlich die exportorientierten Firmen.\nB: Das ist spezifisch genug.",exampleSrc:"A: Some sectors profit, namely the tech sector.\nB: And namely the retail sector?\nA: Namely the export-oriented companies.\nB: That is specific enough.",funFact:"From 'Name' + '-lich' (suffix) + '-t' (adverb). More formal than 'und zwar.' Specifies who or what is meant. Written register for academic and legal texts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"denn",src:"for, because (main clause connector)",pos:"conj",gender:null,note:"Main-clause word order after denn.\n'Er investiert, denn er hat Kapital.'",example:"A: Ich investiere, denn die Zinsen sind niedrig.\nB: Das ist klug, denn die Rendite stimmt.\nA: Wir sparen, denn die Krise ist noch nicht vorbei.\nB: Vorsicht ist wichtig, denn die Lage ist unsicher.",exampleSrc:"A: I invest, because the interest rates are low.\nB: That is wise, because the return is right.\nA: We save, because the crisis is not over yet.\nB: Caution is important, because the situation is uncertain.",funFact:"Coordinating conjunction: main-clause word order follows (unlike weil). Already known from earlier levels, but now part of the full causal connector toolkit alongside da, zumal, naemlich, und zwar."},
{type:"tip",title:"Die Soziale Marktwirtschaft",text:"Germany's economy is neither pure capitalism nor socialism. It is a 'social market economy': free markets with strong social safety nets.\n\nThe government sets the rules (Ordnungspolitik) but does not run companies.\nEmployees have co-determination rights (Mitbestimmungsrechte).\nSocial insurance covers health, pension, unemployment, care, and accidents.\n\nLudwig Erhard designed this system after 1945. It produced the Wirtschaftswunder and remains Germany's economic identity.",deepDive:{title:"Ordnungspolitik vs. Prozesspolitik",text:"Ordnungspolitik: the state sets the framework (competition law, cartel office, consumer protection) but does not intervene in individual markets.\n\nProzesspolitik: direct interventions such as stimulus packages or subsidies. Normally only in times of crisis.\n\nThe ideal: Ordnungspolitik as the rule, Prozesspolitik as the exception. The social market economy lives from this balance."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'In Anbetracht der Tatsache, dass die Exporte sinken, muss die Regierung Massnahmen ergreifen, zumal eine Rezession droht.' Wie viele fortgeschrittene Konstruktionen sind enthalten?",opts:["eine","zwei","vier","drei (in Anbetracht... kausal, NVV Massnahmen ergreifen, zumal kausal)"],ans:"drei (in Anbetracht... kausal, NVV Massnahmen ergreifen, zumal kausal)",hint:"Count: one complex causal opener, one NVV, one emphasizing causal closing."},
{type:"fb",s:"Der Minister bringt seine Bedenken zum {1}.",a:["Ausdruck"],opts:["Ausdruck","Beweis","Betracht","Kenntnis"],hint:"To express something. The fixed noun partner means 'expression.'",sSrc:"The minister expresses his concerns."},
{type:"mc",q:"'Bis 2030 wird die Firma ihre Schulden getilgt haben.' Was sagt dieser Futur-II-Satz voraus?",opts:["Die Firma hat 2030 ihre Schulden zurueckgezahlt","Die Firma zahlt jetzt Schulden zurueck","Die Firma wird ihre Schulden bis 2030 zurueckgezahlt haben","Die Firma sollte Schulden zurueckzahlen"],ans:"Die Firma wird ihre Schulden bis 2030 zurueckgezahlt haben",hint:"werden + Partizip II + haben. A completed future action with a deadline."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"{1} die Konjunktur sich erholt hat, wird der Aufschwung bis 2027 {2} haben, {3} neue Maerkte entstehen.",blanks:{"1":"Da","2":"eingesetzt","3":"zumal"},pool:["Da","eingesetzt","zumal","Weil","setzen","naemlich"],hint:"da-clause + Futur II + zumal-clause. Three constructions in one complex sentence.",sSrc:"Since the economy has recovered, the upswing will have begun by 2027, especially since new markets are emerging."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"zum Ausdruck bringen",src:"to express"},{trg:"in Erwaegung ziehen",src:"to contemplate"},{trg:"Schulden tilgen",src:"to repay debts"},{trg:"Dividenden ausschuetten",src:"to distribute dividends"}]}
]}
]};

export default UNIT_31;
